# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sparta
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author is anonymous, but he probably wrote in the newly independent Hasmonean kingdom after the success of the Maccabean Revolt in the late 2nd century BC.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees was probably written in Hebrew originally.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] However, this original Hebrew has been lost, and the work survives only in translation in Koine Greek in the Septuagint, the Greek version of the Jewish scriptures.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The Septuagint was preserved by Christians as the basis for the Christian Old Testament.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It became part of the deuterocanon in early Christianity.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book is held as canonical scripture today in the Catholic, Eastern Orthodox, and Oriental Orthodox churches (except for the Orthodox Tewahedo).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book is not included in the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh) and is not recognized as canonical by Protestant denominations or any of the major branches of Judaism.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Some Protestants include the book in the biblical apocrypha, as material useful for background and edification but not canonical.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Rabbinic Judaism generally disapproved of the rule of the Hasmonean dynasty, but the book is openly pro-Hasmonean, one of several factors contributing to its lack of enthusiasm within later Judaism.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is best known for its account of the recapture of Jerusalem in the year 164 BC and rededication of the Second Temple: the origin behind the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author of 1 Maccabees is anonymous and unknown.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He wrote in the post-independence Hasmonean kingdom, probably during the reign of High Priest John Hyrcanus (r.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 134–104 BC), with a few scholars suggesting that early in the reign of Alexander Jannaeus (r.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] All agree that the book was written before 63 BC, as the author shows great admiration toward Rome and does not know of the Roman general Pompey conquering Jerusalem and reducing the Hasmonean kingdom to a client state of the Roman Republic in that year.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He was likely a court historian or equivalent.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author appears to be very familiar with Judea and its geography, but appears less well-informed about the wider Hellenistic world.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The entire work is generally considered to be a unity composed by a single author on both philological and thematic grounds, although there are occasional short passages sometimes contested as potentially being added at a later date.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The title "1 Maccabees" is not the original title of the work.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Rather, it comes from the Septuagint, which gave it that title to distinguish it from the other books of the Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In the book itself, "Maccabee" is used solely as a personal title for Judah Maccabee (Latinized as Judas Maccabeus).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Judas's *Maccabee* title is generally tied to the Aramaic word *maqqaba* ("makebet" in modern Hebrew), "hammer" or "sledgehammer".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It is unknown how he got this epithet; most presume it was in recognition of his prowess in battle.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The word "Maccabees" in plural, however, does not appear to have been used until centuries after the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] At first, it was used to describe the martyrs described in 2 Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It later became a title given to the rebels as a whole around the 3rd–5th century AD, hence the Septuagint naming the works as books of the Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] This usage of "Maccabees" as a group-term may have originated in Greek, as no usage of it in Hebrew to refer to the rebels survives from any era earlier than the 19th century.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Eusebius, in his book *Church History*, quotes Origen of Alexandria who says the title of the work was *Sarbēth Sabanaiel*, an enigmatic Greek transliteration from a putative Hebrew original title.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It is thought that the most likely parts are the Aramaic *səpar* ("book"), bêt ("house" or "dynasty"), and 'ēl ("God").
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book was probably originally written in Hebrew.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Both Origen and Jerome claim to have seen a Hebrew text of 1 Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The surviving Greek script has Hebraisms and Hebrew idioms.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It also seems to have been written in Judea where knowledge of Hebrew was more widespread.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] If it really was originally written in Greek, then the author was intentionally imitating Hebrew style in Greek.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book is not written in colloquial "common" Koine Greek of the 2nd century BC, but rather a more archaic style of Greek consciously imitative of the style of older scriptures.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It frequently imitates biblical phraseology and directly cites biblical precedents.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The English equivalent would be writing new books in the style of the King James Version of the Bible.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book is generally classed as a historical book of the Bible.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] While the main focus is a recounting of history, some consider the book to have merit as literary art as well.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The narrative is primarily prose text, but is interrupted by seven poetic sections, which imitate classical Hebrew poetry.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] These include four laments and three hymns of praise.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Various historical documents are included as well, notably of negotiations and letters with the Roman Republic and Hellenistic Sparta.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The setting of the book is about a century and a half after the conquest of Judea by the Greeks under Alexander the Great, after Alexander's empire had been divided so that Judea had become part of the Greek Seleucid Empire.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It tells how the Greek ruler Antiochus IV Epiphanes attempted to suppress the practice of basic Jewish law, resulting in the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book covers the whole of the revolt, from 175 to 134 BC, highlighting how the salvation of the Jewish people in this crisis came through Mattathias' family, particularly his sons, Judas Maccabeus, Jonathan Apphus, and Simon Thassi, and Simon's son, John Hyrcanus.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The doctrine expressed in the book reflects traditional Jewish teaching, without later doctrines found, for example, in 2 Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The First Book of Maccabees also gives a list of Jewish colonies scattered elsewhere through the Mediterranean at the time.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In the first chapter, Alexander the Great conquers the territory of Judea, and is later succeeded by the Seleucid Antiochus IV Epiphanes.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] After successfully invading the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt, Antiochus IV captures Jerusalem and removes the sacred objects from the Temple in Jerusalem, slaughtering many Jews.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He then imposes a tax and establishes a fortress in Jerusalem.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Antiochus then tries to suppress public observance of Jewish laws, in an attempt to secure control over the Jews.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In 168 BC, he desecrates the Temple by setting up an "abomination of desolation" (establishing rites of pagan observance in the Temple, or sacrificing an unclean animal on the altar in the Holy of Holies).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Antiochus forbids both circumcision and possession of Jewish scriptures on pain of death.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He forbids observance of the sabbath and the offering of sacrifices at the Temple.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He also requires Jewish leaders to sacrifice to idols.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] While enforcement may be targeting only Jewish leaders, ordinary Jews were also killed as a warning to others.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Hellenization included the construction of gymnasia in Jerusalem.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Among other effects, this discouraged the Jewish rite of circumcision even further, which had already been officially forbidden; a man's state could not be concealed in the gymnasium, where men trained and socialized in the nude.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] However, 1 Maccabees also insists that there were many Jews who sought out or welcomed the introduction of Greek culture.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] According to the text, some Jewish men even engaged in foreskin restoration in order to pass as fully Greek.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The narrative reports that news of the desolation reaches Mattathias and his five sons, a priestly family who live in Modein.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Mattathias calls upon people loyal to the traditions of Israel to oppose the invaders and the Jewish Hellenizers, and his sons begin a military campaign against them.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] There is one complete loss of a thousand Jews (men, women, and children) to Antiochus when the Jewish defenders refuse to fight on the Sabbath.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The other Jews then reason that, when attacked, they must fight even on the holy day.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In 165 BC the Temple is freed and reconsecrated, so that ritual sacrifices may begin again.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The festival of Hanukkah is instituted by Judas Maccabeus and his brothers to celebrate this event (1 Maccabees 4:59).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] More wars involving Judas and his brothers Simon and Jonathan are reported in chapters 5, 6 and 7.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Chapter 6 reports the last days of Antiochus Epiphanes and the accession of his young son Antiochus V Eupator to the throne.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In chapter 8, Judas seeks an alliance with the Roman Republic, aiming to remove the Greeks.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Jewish historian Uriel Rappaport asserts that "the majority of scholars today accept the authenticity of this document".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] After the death of Judas and a period of lawlessness, he is succeeded by his brother Jonathan Apphus, whose battles with the Greek general Bacchides are recounted in chapter 9.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Jonathan becomes high priest (1 Maccabees 10:20).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Demetrius' death is reported in 1 Maccabees 10:50, and Ptolemy VI Philometor and Alexander Balas, claimant to the Seleucid throne, enter into an agreement under which Alexander marries Cleopatra Thea, Ptolemy's daughter (1 Maccabees 10:58).
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Maccabees does not mention the involvement of the mercenaries who are mentioned in other accounts, whereas other accounts do not mention the Jewish involvement.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Ultimately the relationship between Jonathan and Demetrius breaks down: Maccabees' opinion is that Demetrius "broke his word about all that he had promised; he became estranged from Jonathan and did not repay the favors that Jonathan had done him, but treated him very harshly".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Proposed alliances with Rome and with Areus of Sparta are covered in 1 Maccabees 12:1–23.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Jonathan's capture in 143 BC, having been double-crossed by Diodotus Tryphon, is recorded in 1 Maccabees 12:48.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Simon follows Jonathan as the next Jewish leader "in place of Judas and your brother Jonathan", taking on civil, military and liturgical roles: "great high priest, governor, and leader of the Jews".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Simon fortifies Jerusalem (1 Maccabees 13:10) and secures the reoccupation of Joppa (1 Maccabees 13:11), leading the people in peace and prosperity until he is murdered by agents of Ptolemy, son of Abubus, who had been named governor of the region by the Macedonian Greeks.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The period of peace and prosperity is celebrated in a biblical-style poetic passage, the "Eulogy of Simon", which Rappaport considers to be "one of the most important poetic passages in 1 Maccabees".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Simon is succeeded by his son, John, referred to by Josephus as John Hyrcanus.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author propagates "Hasmonean propaganda" in the sense of upholding the righteousness of the Hasmoneans and their just claim to rule the Hasmonean kingdom.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The Hasmoneans were not an obvious choice to be rulers; they did not descend from the priestly line of Zadok that had taken the office of High Priest for generations at the point of the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author seeks to promote the view that the Hasmoneans were indeed God's new chosen and would-be rulers in line with heroes of the Hebrew Bible.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Various passages call back to Biblical passages such as Joshua's conquests or the battle of David and Goliath and equate the Hasmoneans' deeds with the earlier stories.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Antipathy toward the Seleucid-friendly Hellenizing Jews is unsurprising, as they were enemies in war, but 1 Maccabees extends criticism to internal Jewish opponents of the Hasmoneans as well.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In 1 Maccabees, those dissatisfied with the Hasmoneans "hated their nation" as a whole; the Hasmoneans were equated with Judea itself.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Jews who complain about Judas's activities "bring to the king an accusation against the people".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book dismisses a defeat suffered by other commanders named Joseph and Azariah as because "they did not listen to Judas and his brothers.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] But they did not belong to the family of those men through whom deliverance was given to Israel." All of this makes clear that God has specifically chosen a new dynasty to rule Judea, the Hasmoneans.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] While the book holds all the Hasmoneans in high regard, it praises Simon Thassi in particular, the person who would pass the High Priesthood to his sons and establish the dynasty.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] In Chapter 2, there is a line from a dying Mattathias who tells his sons to always listen to Simon and that "he shall be your father", seemingly praising him even over Judas.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Chapter 14 also features a long panegyric praising Simon as a worthy leader.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The school of philosophy seen in 1 Maccabees is often thought to be a predecessor to the philosophy of the Sadducees in later eras.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Notably, the author makes no reference to the idea of a bodily resurrection, which the Sadducees opposed.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] That said, contemporary textual sources of the Sadducees are scant, so it is difficult to know for sure.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book also comes across as dismissive of martyrdom and passive approaches to resistance, seeing such gestures as futile and pointless.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Some scholars go even farther than dismissive; Jonathan A.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Goldstein wrote that the author had "considerable contempt for martyrs".
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] For the author, bold military action while living is the proper response to oppression.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The author sees the revolt as divinely ordained, but downplays direct divine intervention such as miracles.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Rather, the author interprets events as God using the military genius of Judas Maccabeus and his brothers as the instrument to achieve the liberation of Judea.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] One of the most notable and unusual aspects of the book of 1 Maccabees by absence is the lack of any direct mention of God.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] No angels or miracles come to save the Jews; rather, it is the divinely-approved firm leadership of the Hasmoneans that leads to victory.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book 2 Maccabees, preserved with 1 Maccabees in the Septuagint, provides a striking contrast in theology, and the works are often compared.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 2 Maccabees interprets the misfortunes of the Jews as God's punishment for their own sins; the author of 1 Maccabees depicts the problems as due to the external evil of Antiochus IV and his generals, not as a cleansing ordeal that was in some sense divine will.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book draws a sharp contrast between Jews and Gentiles, similar to the books of Ezra and Nehemiah.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The persecution of Antiochus IV presumably radicalized the Jews.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] That said, the author is still proud of forging alliances with others, citing negotiations with the Roman Republic and Sparta.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Uriel Rappaport called it emblematic of Hasmonean politics, in general: that the Hasmonean state was an explicitly Jewish one that sought to separate itself from polytheism, yet was pragmatic and sought allies where they could be found.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is the most extensive source of information on events in Judea from 175 to 135 BC.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It has traditionally been considered highly trustworthy, though it is, to some extent, the "official" version of history from the Hasmonean and Maccabean points of view.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Bezalel Bar-Kochva praises it as among the better military historiography of the period.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He argues that the author was likely an eyewitness to at least some of the battles described, given his great accuracy and plausibility in describing terrain and troop movements, and was able to obtain firsthand accounts from others in interviews.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He also cites the fact that it makes various "admissions against interest" such as openly describing rebel military defeats, unlike 2 Maccabees, which obscures or omits such matters.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Goldstein argues that the book was imitative of older scriptures not merely in linguistic style, but also in content; that is, the author adjusted or invented events to make them fit biblical parallels better.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Pope Damasus I's Council of Rome in 382, if the Gelasian Decree is correctly associated with it, issued a Christian biblical canon identical to the list given at Trent, including the two books of Maccabees.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Origen of Alexandria (253), Augustine of Hippo (c.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 397 AD), Pope Innocent I (405), Synod of Hippo (393), the Council of Carthage (397), the Council of Carthage (419), the Apostolic Canons, the Council of Florence (1442), and the Council of Trent (1546) listed the first two books of Maccabees as canonical.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] During the Protestant Reformation, the book—along with other books in the Catholic deuterocanon—was classed as biblical apocrypha in Protestantism: material useful for background but not canonical.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The 1643 Westminster Confession of Faith declared that the books "are of no authority in the Church of God, not to be any otherwise approved", for example.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The book was never included in the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh) and is not canonical by any mainstream movements of Judaism.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Later Jewish leaders viewed the rule of the Hasmonean dynasty poorly for several reasons, and a document so openly celebratory of them was problematic.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Even in stories set during the Maccabean period, references to Judas by name were explicitly removed to avoid hero-worship of the Hasmonean line.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The Jewish historian Josephus of the 1st century AD almost certainly read 1 Maccabees in Greek.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He extensively uses the first thirteen chapters of it in Books 12 and 13 of his work *Jewish Antiquities*, paraphrasing it directly in parts, although supplementing it with other Greek histories such as Nicolaus of Damascus.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] He may also have consulted it for Book 1 of *The Jewish War*.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It is not known whether Josephus's copy of 1 Maccabees was missing the final three chapters, or he simply found a better source for that era of history.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is only very rarely quoted or referenced by the Church Fathers in the era of early Christianity.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] When Christians of the Roman Empire discussed the Maccabees, it was usually in reference to the "Maccabean martyrs" described in 2 Maccabees 6 and 2 Maccabees 7, as they were seen as models and precursors to Christian martyrs.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] As 1 Maccabees has very little to say about the martyrs, it correspondingly was not cited or read.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] During the Crusades, Pope Urban II and other church leaders used 1 Maccabees to justify the concept of holy war against the Muslim kingdoms controlling the holy city of Jerusalem.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Admired crusaders such as Baldwin I and Godfrey of Bouillon were explicitly compared to Judas Maccabeus, and material from 1 Maccabees was quoted in regards to their deeds.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees was also cited during the 11th–12th century Investiture Controversy concerning whether monarchs had the authority to appoint bishops, or only the Pope.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees includes passages describing the appointment of Jonathan and Simon by Seleucid authorities, so it was generally cited by the side of those who favored royal appointment of bishops.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] 1 Maccabees is part of the intertestamental Apocrypha section of the Bible used in the Lutheran Churches and the Anglican Communion.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Scripture readings from the Apocrypha are included in the lectionaries of the Lutheran Churches.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] With regard to Anglicanism, in the Church of England's lectionary of 1922 in the *Book of Common Prayer*, 1st Maccabees is appointed annually to be read in late summer/early autumn.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The texts regarding the martyrdoms under Antiochus IV in 1 Maccabees and 2 Maccabees are read by Anabaptist Christians, who faced persecution in their history.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] As noted above, if ancient manuscripts of the hypothesized original Hebrew version existed, they have been lost.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The Greek text is extant in two of the three oldest codices of the Greek Septuagint: the Codex Sinaiticus and Codex Alexandrinus.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Pre-modern translations of the work were made in Latin, Syriac, and Armenian.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] The Latin translation is sometimes useful to identify certain changes made by Lucian of Antioch to the Greek text.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] With the advent of the printing press that obviated the need for scribes to manually and repeatedly copy such works, 1 Maccabees became more widely available.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] It was included in standard printed Christian Bibles in the deuterocanon section.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] A Greek version of the text was printed for the first time in 1514–1517 in the Complutensian Polyglot Bible.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] Werner Kappler published a critical edition of the Greek text in 1936, an eclectic compilation of the various surviving manuscripts and the best construction of the original text.
[src:sparta/1-maccabees] More recent English language versions of the Bible which contain 1 Maccabees include the New Revised Standard Version (NRSV), Good News Translation (GNT), New American Bible, Revised Edition (NABRE), and the Knox Bible.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The **464 BC Spartan earthquake** occurred along the Sparta fault in the year 464 BC destroying much of what was Sparta and many other city-states in ancient Greece.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Historical sources suggest that the death toll may have been as high as 20,000, although modern scholars suggest that this figure is likely an exaggeration.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The earthquake gave Spartan helots an opportunity to revolt against their aristocratic rulers, and the Spartan Pericleidas was sent to the Athenians to seek their aid.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Their immediate dismissal upon arrival is said to have been a key event that led up to the First Peloponnesian War.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Sparta was located on what is currently called the Hellenic arc which is predisposed to large seismic activity due to the convergence and subduction of the African plate beneath the Aegean Sea plate.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The convergent and subduction of these plates are also seen in the geographical landscape in present-day Greece with large mountain ranges as well as many islands and the lands drop off into the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Present day Greece still experiences seismic activity regularly; however, it is usually much milder than the one felt in 464 BC.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Accounts of the earthquake and its consequences are based on only a few often unreliable historical sources, specifically the writings of Strabo, Pausanias, Plutarch, and Thucydides.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] As there is little recorded about the earthquake itself in contemporary records, it is difficult to judge the exact epicenter and magnitude of the event.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] However, the earthquake is believed to have been 'medium to large' according to many historians and occurred due to movement on a fault near the Taygetus Mountains.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] A 1991 study attempted to locate the fault responsible for the event and estimate the magnitude of the earthquake based on satellite imagery and fieldwork.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The authors of the study conclude that if the 464 BC event took place along the fault whose scarp they identified, its magnitude would have been approximately 7.2 on the surface-wave magnitude scale.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Due to the lack of proper infrastructure and seismic engineering knowledge during this time casualties were originally thought to be very high with some contemporary sources believing the death toll to be around 20,000.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] However, modern scholars believe this might be an exaggeration due to the fact that at the time the city was relatively small and spread out, with most buildings being one floor and constructed from wood or sun-baked brick making it hard to believe that casualties could have been so high.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The lack of detailed population records, coupled with flight of survivors to other areas, may have contributed to the uncertainty, as it can today.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] In such a catastrophic earthquake, it is also unlikely that a number of the anecdotal tales from the time could be true, such as the Spartan king Archidamus leading the Spartan army out of the city to safety.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Regardless of the exact death toll, there was some destruction, and the helots, the serf class in Spartan society, took advantage of this moment to rise in rebellion.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The 464 BC Sparta earthquake is marked by scholars as one of the key events that led to the First Peloponnesian War.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] However, according to Thucydides, the ancient Greek chronicler of the Peloponnesian War, Sparta had already decided to invade Attica when the earthquake struck.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] In the aftermath of the earthquake, the helots and various Messenian subjects of Sparta revolted; Sparta invoked the aid of other Greek cities to put down the rebellion, which they were obliged to help in accordance with the alliance.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Athens, whose aid the Spartans sought because of their "reputed experience in siege operations," sent approximately 4,000 hoplites under the leadership of Cimon, but this contingent was sent back to Athens, while those from other cities were allowed to stay.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The Athenians were insulted, and therefore repudiated their alliance with Sparta.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Once the uprising was put down, some of the surviving rebels fled to Athens, which settled them at Naupactus on the strategically important Corinthian Gulf.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] The alliance between Sparta and Athens was never revived, and disagreements continued to intensify until the outbreak of war in 460 BC.
[src:sparta/464-bc-sparta-earthquake] Since the Helot population used the earthquake as their opportunity to rebel, the Spartans were forced to wait to reform their society until after they had suppressed the Helots.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The work is usually referred to as *Lewis and Short* after the names of its editors, Charlton T.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] It was derived from the 1850 English translation by Ethan Allen Andrews of an earlier Latin–German dictionary, *Wörterbuch der Lateinischen Sprache*, by the German philologist Wilhelm Freund, in turn based on I.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Scheller’s Latin–German dictionary of 1783.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The Andrews translation was partially revised by Freund himself, then by Henry Drisler, and was finally edited by Short and Lewis.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The division of labour between the two editors was remarkably unequal.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] In 1890 Lewis published a heavily abridged version of the dictionary, entitled *An Elementary Latin Dictionary*, for the use of students.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Sometimes called the *Elementary Lewis*, it is still in print today.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The adoption of the book by Oxford University Press was the result of the failure of its own project to create a new Latin–English dictionary in 1875.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Henry Nettleship and John Mayor had been commissioned to produce a new Latin dictionary based on a fresh reading of the sources, but after Mayor withdrew from the project, Nettleship was unable to complete it on his own; he eventually published his research as notes on Lewis and Short.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] While the Press had earlier published John Riddle's 1835 translation of Scheller's Latin–German dictionary, this was a much more expensive book.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The Press thus adopted *Harpers' Latin Dictionary* as a stopgap measure, paying Harper and Brothers 10 per cent royalties.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Harper and Brothers sold its rights to the American Book Company in 1899, shortly before its bankruptcy.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] From the time of its publication, many scholars have criticized the dictionary for its errors and inconsistencies.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Because of various circumstances, however, no replacement was attempted until 1933, with the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, which was completed in 1983.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] However, the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* stops at 200CE.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The dictionary's full text (year 1879) is available online at numerous websites.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Among classicists "never a very good dictionary", Lewis and Short has been largely superseded by the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, called the *OLD* for short.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short incorporated material from existing Latin dictionaries; the *OLD*, by contrast, started from scratch, following procedures similar to those of the well-regarded *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Thanks to the increased availability of modern editions, the *OLD* editors had access to a larger variety of classical works.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] It was decided in the *OLD'*s planning that the *OLD* would not encompass Latin written later than AD 200, with a few exceptions.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Although classicists still consult Lewis and Short, they tend to prefer the *OLD*.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short retains value for its refined sense of the nuances of English diction as it interfaces with Latin diction (in contrast with *OLD*'s preference for plainer diction) and also for the sensitivity of its quotations from classical texts, reflecting this.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short's primary focus is on classical Latin, not medieval Latin.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Nevertheless, Lewis and Short is consulted by medievalists, renaissance specialists, and early modernists, as it includes some late and medieval Latin, if somewhat inconsistently, and classical Latin usages are very relevant in medieval Latin.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The *Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources* supplements Lewis and Short for medieval Latin vocabulary.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Another dictionary focused on medieval Latin is J.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] Niermeyer's **Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus**, first published in 1976, with an enhanced second edition in year 2002, about 1500 pages.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] On occasion people confuse Lewis and Short (or L&S) with Liddell and Scott, its Greek counterpart, entitled *A Greek–English Lexicon*.
[src:sparta/a-latin-dictionary] The 1925 and later editions of Liddell and Scott are commonly referred to by the abbreviation *LSJ* after the names of its editors Liddell, Scott and the editor of the 1925 revision, Henry Stuart Jones.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] Abonoteichos was a town on the coast of Paphlagonia, memorable as the birthplace of the infamous fortuneteller Alexander Abonoteichites, founder of the cult of Glycon, of whom Lucian left an amusing account in the treatise bearing his name.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] According to Lucian, Alexander petitioned the Roman emperor (probably Antoninus Pius) that the name of his native place should be changed from Abonoteichos to **Ionopolis**; and whether the emperor granted the request or not, we know that the town was called Ionopolis in later times.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] Not only does this name occur in Marcian of Heraclea and Hierocles, but on coins of the time of Antoninus and Lucius Verus we find the legend Ionopoliton (ΙΩΝΟΠΟΛΙΤΩΝ), as well as Abonoteichiton (ΑΒΩΝΟΤΕΙΧΙΤΩΝ).
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] The modern Turkish name İnebolu is evidently a corruption of Ionopolis.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] It was the site of a 2nd-century AD temple of Apollo.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] It was important enough in the Roman province of Paphlagonia to become a suffragan bishopric of the Metropolitan of its capital Gangra, but faded later.
[src:sparta/abonoteichos] The diocese was nominally revived as a Latin Catholic titular bishopric under the name Ionopolis, which was spelled **Jonopolis** in the Roman Curia (besides Italian *Gionopoli*) from 1929 to 1971.
[src:sparta/abraham] The story of the life of Abraham, as told in the narrative of the Book of Genesis in the Hebrew Bible, revolves around the themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:sparta/abraham] He is said to have been called by God to leave the house of his father Terah and settle in the land of Canaan, which God now promises to Abraham and his progeny.
[src:sparta/abraham] This promise is subsequently inherited by Isaac, Abraham's son by his wife Sarah, while Isaac's half-brother Ishmael is also promised that he will be the founder of a great nation.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham purchases a tomb (the Cave of the Patriarchs) at Hebron to be Sarah's grave, thus establishing his right to the land; and, in the second generation, his heir Isaac is married to a woman from his own kin to earn his parents' approval.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham later marries Keturah and has six more sons; but, on his death, when he is buried beside Sarah, it is Isaac who receives "all Abraham's goods" while the other sons receive only "gifts".
[src:sparta/abraham] Most scholars view the patriarchal age, along with the Exodus, as a late literary construct that does not relate to any particular historical era.
[src:sparta/abraham] Many scholars believe the Abraham traditions developed orally over centuries, before being incorporated into the Book of Genesis during the Persian period of Yehud, where they helped shape post-exilic Jewish identity and support competing claims to the land.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Abraham cycle (Genesis 11:27–Genesis 25:11) unfolds as a narrative of mounting tension, centered on the conflict between God's promise that Abram would father a lineage and become the ancestor of numerous nations, and a succession of crises that jeopardize this divine commitment.
[src:sparta/abraham] The storytelling method used here is the “obstacle story,” a literary device renowned for its enduring and universal popularity across cultures and eras.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Abraham cycle is not structured by a unified plot centered on a conflict and its resolution or a problem and its solution.
[src:sparta/abraham] The episodes are often only loosely linked, and the sequence is not always logical.
[src:sparta/abraham] The story portrays Abraham gradually assuming the role of the ideal religious person amid themes of blessing and promise, especially the promise of progeny and land.
[src:sparta/abraham] These themes form "narrative programs" set out in Genesis 11:27–31 concerning the sterility of Sarah and Genesis 12:1–3 in which Abraham is ordered to leave the land of his birth for the land God will show him.
[src:sparta/abraham] Terah, the ninth in descent from Noah, was the father of Abram, Nahor, Haran (Hebrew: הָרָן *Hārān*) and Sarah.
[src:sparta/abraham] Haran was the father of Lot, who was Abram's nephew; the family lived in Ur of the Chaldees.
[src:sparta/abraham] Haran died there while Terah was still alive.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram married Sarah (Sarai) but, unlike Nahor and his wife Milcah, they were childless.
[src:sparta/abraham] Genesis 11 records that Terah, Abram, Sarai, and Lot departed for Canaan, but settled in a place named Haran (Hebrew: חָרָן *Ḥārān*), where Terah died at the age of 205.
[src:sparta/abraham] Then the narrative in Genesis 12 shows that God told Abram to leave his country and his kindred, and go to a land that God would show him, and promised to make of him a great nation, bless him, make his name great, bless them that bless him, and curse them who may curse him.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram was 75 years old when he and Sarai left Haran with his nephew Lot, and their possessions and people that they had acquired, and they traveled to Shechem in Canaan.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram built an altar to God in Shechem, and later he built another altar between Bethel and Ai.
[src:sparta/abraham] From there the party travelled to the Negev, or to the south.
[src:sparta/abraham] According to some exegetes, like Nahmanides, Abram was actually born in Haran and he later relocated to Ur, while some of his family remained in Haran.
[src:sparta/abraham] There was a severe famine in the land of Canaan, so that Abram, Lot, and their households traveled to Egypt.
[src:sparta/abraham] On the way Abram told Sarai to tell the Egyptians she was his sister, so that the Egyptians would not kill him.
[src:sparta/abraham] When they entered Egypt, the Pharaoh's officials praised Sarai's beauty to Pharaoh, and they took her into the palace and gave Abram goods in exchange.
[src:sparta/abraham] God afflicted Pharaoh and his household with plagues, which led Pharaoh to try to find out what was wrong.
[src:sparta/abraham] Upon discovering that Sarai was a married woman, Pharaoh demanded that Abram and Sarai leave, escorting them to the frontier.
[src:sparta/abraham] When they lived for a while in the Negev after being banished from Egypt and came back to the Bethel and Ai area, Abram's and Lot's sizable herds occupied the same pastures.
[src:sparta/abraham] This became a problem for the herdsmen, who were assigned to each family's cattle.
[src:sparta/abraham] The conflicts between herdsmen had become so troublesome that Abram suggested that Lot choose a separate area, either on the left hand or on the right hand, that there be no conflict between them.
[src:sparta/abraham] Lot decided to go eastward to the plain of Jordan, where the land was well watered everywhere as far as Zoara, and he dwelled in the cities of the plain toward Sodom.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram went south to Hebron and settled in the plain of Mamre, where he built another altar to worship God.
[src:sparta/abraham] During the rebellion of the Jordan River cities, Sodom and Gomorrah, against Elam, Abram's nephew, Lot, was taken prisoner along with his entire household by the invading Elamite forces.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Elamite army came to collect the spoils of war, after having just defeated the king of Sodom's armies.
[src:sparta/abraham] Lot and his family, at the time, were settled on the outskirts of the Kingdom of Sodom which made them a visible target.
[src:sparta/abraham] One person who escaped capture came and told Abram what happened.
[src:sparta/abraham] Once Abram received this news, he immediately assembled 318 trained servants.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram's force headed north in pursuit of the Elamite army, who were already worn down from the Battle of Siddim.
[src:sparta/abraham] When they caught up with them at Dan, Abram devised a battle plan by splitting his group into more than one unit, and launched a night raid.
[src:sparta/abraham] Not only were they able to free the captives, Abram's unit chased and slaughtered the Elamite King Chedorlaomer at Hobah, just north of Damascus.
[src:sparta/abraham] They freed Lot, as well as his household and possessions, and recovered all of the goods from Sodom that had been taken.
[src:sparta/abraham] Upon Abram's return, Sodom's king came out to meet with him in the Valley of Shaveh, the "king's dale".
[src:sparta/abraham] Also, Melchizedek king of Salem (Jerusalem), a priest of El Elyon, brought out bread and wine and blessed Abram and God.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram then gave Melchizedek a tenth of everything.
[src:sparta/abraham] The king of Sodom then offered to let Abram keep all the possessions if he would merely return his people.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram declined to accept anything other than the share to which his allies were entitled.
[src:sparta/abraham] Some time after these events, the voice of the LORD came to Abram in a vision, promising him a "reward", namely a son, and repeating the promise of the land and descendants as numerous as the stars.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram was childless until then, and had anticipated that Eliezer of Damascus, head of his household, would inherit his estate on his death.
[src:sparta/abraham] He was to be rewarded in virtue of his trust in God.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram and God then made a covenant ceremony, and God told Abram of the future bondage of his people "in a land that is not theirs", referring to Egypt.
[src:sparta/abraham] God then described to Abram the land that his offspring would claim: the land of the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites, Hittites, Perizzites, the Rephaim, Amorites, Canaanites, Girgashites, and Jebusites.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram and Sarai tried to make sense of how he would become a progenitor of nations, because after 10 years of living in Canaan, no child had been born.
[src:sparta/abraham] Sarai then offered her Egyptian slave, Hagar, to Abram with the intention that she would bear him a son.
[src:sparta/abraham] After Hagar found she was pregnant, she began to despise her mistress, Sarai.
[src:sparta/abraham] Sarai responded by mistreating Hagar, and Hagar fled into the wilderness.
[src:sparta/abraham] An angel spoke with Hagar at the fountain on the way to Shur.
[src:sparta/abraham] He instructed her to return to Abram's camp and that her son would be "a wild ass of a man; his hand shall be against every man, and every man's hand against him; and he shall dwell in the face of all his brethren." She was told to call her son Ishmael.
[src:sparta/abraham] Hagar then called God who spoke to her "El-roi", ("Thou God seest me": KJV).
[src:sparta/abraham] From that day onward, the well was called Beer-lahai-roi, ("The well of him that liveth and seeth me": KJV margin), located between Kadesh and Bered.
[src:sparta/abraham] She then did as she was instructed by returning to her mistress in order to have her child.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram was 86 years of age when Ishmael was born.
[src:sparta/abraham] Thirteen years later, when Abram was 99 years of age, God appeared to Abram again and called upon him to be "perfect" or "blameless", so that God could make a covenant with him.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abram fell or bowed to the ground in a gesture of reverence, and God gave Abram a new name: he was now to be called "Abraham".
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham means "father of a multitude": he would be "a father of many nations".
[src:sparta/abraham] The new name denotes a new stage in Abraham's life.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham then received God's instructions concerning circumcision.
[src:sparta/abraham] God also declared Sarai's new name to be "Sarah", blessed her, and told Abraham, "I will give thee a son also of her".
[src:sparta/abraham] Immediately after Abraham's encounter with God, he had his entire household of men, including himself (age 99) and Ishmael (age 13), circumcised.
[src:sparta/abraham] Not long afterward, during the heat of the day, Abraham had been sitting at the entrance of his tent by the terebinths of Mamre.
[src:sparta/abraham] He looked up and saw three men in the presence of God.
[src:sparta/abraham] Then he ran and bowed to the ground to welcome them.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham then offered to wash their feet and fetch them a morsel of bread, to which they assented.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham rushed to Sarah's tent to order ash cakes made from choice flour, then he ordered a servant-boy to prepare a choice calf.
[src:sparta/abraham] When all was prepared, he set curds, milk and the calf before them, waiting on them, under a tree, as they ate.
[src:sparta/abraham] One of the visitors told Abraham that upon his return next year, Sarah would have a son.
[src:sparta/abraham] While at the tent entrance, Sarah overheard what was said and she laughed to herself about the prospect of having a child at their ages.
[src:sparta/abraham] The visitor inquired of Abraham why Sarah laughed at bearing a child at her age, as nothing is too hard for God.
[src:sparta/abraham] After eating, Abraham and the three visitors got up.
[src:sparta/abraham] Accompanied by Abraham, the visitors walked over to the peak that overlooked the "cities of the plain" to discuss the fate of Sodom and Gomorrah for their detestable sins that were so great, they moved God to action.
[src:sparta/abraham] Because of God's promise to Abraham regarding his destiny, God revealed plans to assess what these cities have done and confer judgment on them.
[src:sparta/abraham] At this point, the two other visitors left for Sodom.
[src:sparta/abraham] Then Abraham turned to God and pleaded decrementally with Him (from fifty persons to less) that "if there were at least ten righteous men found in the city, would not God spare the city?" For the sake of ten righteous people, God declared that he would not destroy the city.
[src:sparta/abraham] When the two visitors arrived in Sodom to conduct their report, they planned on staying in the city square.
[src:sparta/abraham] However, Abraham's nephew, Lot, met with them and strongly insisted that these two "men" stay at his house for the night.
[src:sparta/abraham] A rally of men stood outside of Lot's home and demanded that Lot bring out his guests so that they may "know" (v.
[src:sparta/abraham] However, Lot objected and offered his virgin daughters who had not "known" (v.
[src:sparta/abraham] They rejected that notion and sought to break down Lot's door to get to his male guests, thus confirming the wickedness of the city and portending their imminent destruction.
[src:sparta/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham went to the place where he stood before God.
[src:sparta/abraham] He "looked out toward Sodom and Gomorrah" and saw what became of the cities of the plain, where not even "ten righteous" (v.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham moved to live between Kadesh and Shur, settling in Gerar, later associated with the Philistines".
[src:sparta/abraham] While he was living in there, Abraham openly claimed that Sarah was his sister, and she confirmed this assertion, leading King Abimelech to call for Sarah to be brought to him.
[src:sparta/abraham] God then came to Abimelech in a dream and declared that taking her would result in his death, because she was a man's wife.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abimelech had not laid hands on her, so he inquired if he would also slay a righteous nation, especially since Abraham and Sarah had claimed that they were siblings.
[src:sparta/abraham] In response, God told Abimelech that he did indeed have a blameless heart and that is why he continued to exist.
[src:sparta/abraham] However, should he not return the wife of Abraham back to him, God would surely destroy Abimelech and his entire household.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abimelech was informed that Abraham was a prophet who would pray for him.
[src:sparta/abraham] Early next morning, Abimelech informed his servants of his dream and approached Abraham inquiring as to why he had brought such great guilt upon his kingdom.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham stated that he thought there was no fear of God in that place, and that they might kill him for his wife.
[src:sparta/abraham] Further, Abimelech gave Abraham a thousand pieces of silver to serve as Sarah's vindication before all.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham then prayed for Abimelech and his household, since God had stricken the women with infertility because of the taking of Sarah.
[src:sparta/abraham] Two incidents follow in which Abraham and Abimelech resolve issues by agreement.
[src:sparta/abraham] Firstly, Abimelech, supported by Phicol, the chief of his troops, secures from the patriarch an agreement that he will act honestly in his dealings with Abimelech and his descendants, reciprocating the manner in which Abimelech says he has treated Abraham.
[src:sparta/abraham] Subsequently, a specific issue arises in relation to a well which Abraham has dug but which Abimelech's servants have taken over.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abimelech and Phicol approached Abraham because of a dispute over the well.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham reproached Abimelech due to his servants' aggressive attacks and the seizing of the well.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abimelech claimed ignorance of the incident.
[src:sparta/abraham] Then Abraham offered a pact by providing sheep and oxen to Abimelech.
[src:sparta/abraham] Further, to attest that Abraham was the one who had dug the well, he also gave Abimelech seven ewes for proof.
[src:sparta/abraham] Because of this sworn oath, they called the place of this well Beersheba.
[src:sparta/abraham] After Abimelech and Phicol headed back to Philistia, Abraham planted a tamarisk grove in Beersheba and called upon "the name of the LORD, the everlasting God".
[src:sparta/abraham] As had been prophesied at Mamre the previous year, Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham, on the first anniversary of the covenant of circumcision.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham was "an hundred years old" when his son, whom he named Isaac, was born, and he circumcised him when he was eight days old.
[src:sparta/abraham] During the celebration, however, Sarah found Ishmael mocking; an observation that would begin to clarify the birthright of Isaac.
[src:sparta/abraham] Ishmael was fourteen years old when Abraham's son Isaac was born to Sarah.
[src:sparta/abraham] When she found Ishmael teasing Isaac, Sarah told Abraham to send both Ishmael and Hagar away.
[src:sparta/abraham] She declared that Ishmael would not share in Isaac's inheritance.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham was greatly distressed by his wife's words and sought the advice of his God.
[src:sparta/abraham] God told Abraham not to be distressed but to do as his wife commanded.
[src:sparta/abraham] God reassured Abraham that "in Isaac shall seed be called to thee." He also said Ishmael would make a nation, "because he is thy seed".
[src:sparta/abraham] Early the next morning, Abraham brought Hagar and Ishmael out together.
[src:sparta/abraham] He gave her bread and water and sent them away.
[src:sparta/abraham] The two wandered in the wilderness of Beersheba until her bottle of water was completely consumed.
[src:sparta/abraham] In a moment of despair, she burst into tears.
[src:sparta/abraham] After God heard the boy's voice, an angel of the Lord confirmed to Hagar that he would become a great nation, and will be "living on his sword".
[src:sparta/abraham] A well of water then appeared so that it saved their lives.
[src:sparta/abraham] As the boy grew, he became a skilled archer living in the wilderness of Paran.
[src:sparta/abraham] Eventually his mother found a wife for Ishmael from her home country, the land of Egypt.
[src:sparta/abraham] At some point in Isaac's youth, Abraham was commanded by God to offer his son up as a sacrifice in the land of Moriah.
[src:sparta/abraham] The patriarch traveled three days until he came to the mount that God told him of.
[src:sparta/abraham] He then commanded the servants to remain while he and Isaac proceeded alone into the mount.
[src:sparta/abraham] Isaac carried the wood upon which he would be sacrificed.
[src:sparta/abraham] Along the way, Isaac asked his father where the animal for the burnt offering was, to which Abraham replied "God will provide himself a lamb for a burnt offering".
[src:sparta/abraham] Just as Abraham was about to sacrifice his son, he was interrupted by the angel of the Lord, and he saw behind him a "ram caught in a thicket by his horns", which he sacrificed instead of his son.
[src:sparta/abraham] The place was later named as Jehovah-jireh.
[src:sparta/abraham] For his obedience he received another promise of numerous descendants and abundant prosperity.
[src:sparta/abraham] After this event, Abraham went to Beersheba.
[src:sparta/abraham] Sarah died, and Abraham buried her in the Cave of the Patriarchs (the "cave of Machpelah"), near Hebron which he had purchased along with the adjoining field from Ephron the Hittite.
[src:sparta/abraham] After the death of Sarah, Abraham took another wife, a concubine named Keturah, and together they had six sons: Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham lived to see Isaac marry Rebekah, and to see the birth of his twin grandsons Jacob and Esau.
[src:sparta/abraham] He died at age 175, and was buried in the cave of Machpelah by his sons Isaac and Ishmael.
[src:sparta/abraham] In the early and middle 20th century, leading archaeologists such as William F.
[src:sparta/abraham] Ernest Wright and biblical scholars such as Albrecht Alt and John Bright believed that the patriarchs and matriarchs were either real individuals or believable composites of people who lived in the "patriarchal age", the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:sparta/abraham] However, in the 1970s, new arguments concerning Israel's past and the biblical texts challenged these views; these arguments can be found in Thomas L.
[src:sparta/abraham] Thompson's *The Historicity of the Patriarchal Narratives* (1974), and John Van Seters' *Abraham in History and Tradition* (1975).
[src:sparta/abraham] Thompson, a literary scholar, based his argument on archaeology and ancient texts.
[src:sparta/abraham] His thesis centered on the lack of compelling evidence that the patriarchs lived in the 2nd millennium BCE, and noted how certain biblical texts reflected first millennium conditions and concerns.
[src:sparta/abraham] Van Seters examined the patriarchal stories and argued that their names, social milieu, and messages strongly suggested that they were Iron Age creations.
[src:sparta/abraham] Van Seters' and Thompson's works were a paradigm shift in biblical scholarship and archaeology, which gradually led scholars to no longer consider the patriarchal narratives as historical.
[src:sparta/abraham] Some conservative scholars attempted to defend the Patriarchal narratives in the following years, but this has not found acceptance among scholars.
[src:sparta/abraham] By the beginning of the 21st century, archaeologists had stopped trying to recover any context that would make Abraham, Isaac or Jacob credible historical figures.
[src:sparta/abraham] At some stage the oral traditions became part of the written tradition of the Pentateuch; a majority of scholars believe this stage belongs to the Persian period, roughly 520–320 BCE.
[src:sparta/abraham] The mechanisms by which this came about remain unknown, but there are currently at least two hypotheses.
[src:sparta/abraham] The completion of the Torah and its elevation to the centre of post-Exilic Judaism was as much or more about combining older texts as writing new ones – the final Pentateuch was based on existing traditions.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Book of Isaiah similarly testifies to tension between the people of Judah and the returning post-Exilic Jews (the "gôlâ"), stating that God is the father of Israel and that Israel's history begins with the Exodus and not with Abraham.
[src:sparta/abraham] According to Nissim Amzallag, the Book of Genesis portrays Abraham as having an Amorite origin, arguing that the patriarch's provenance from the region of Harran as described in Genesis 11:31 associates him with the territory of the Amorite homeland.
[src:sparta/abraham] He also notes parallels between the biblical narrative and the Amorite migration into the Southern Levant in the 2nd millennium BCE.
[src:sparta/abraham] Alan Millard argues that the name Abram is of Amorite origin and that it is attested in Mari as *ʾabī-rām*.
[src:sparta/abraham] He also suggests that the Patriarch's name corresponds to a form typical of the Middle Bronze Age and not of later periods.
[src:sparta/abraham] Some papers identify Abraham with the Amorite chieftain Abum, and his son Ishmael with Sumulael.
[src:sparta/abraham] The orientalist Mario Liverani has proposed to see in the name Abraham the eponymous ancestor of a 13th-century BCE tribe, the Raham, mentioned in a stele of Seti I found at Beth-Shean and dating back to around 1289 BCE.
[src:sparta/abraham] The tribe probably lived in the area surrounding or close to Beth-Shean, in Galilee (the stele in fact refers to battles that took place in the area).
[src:sparta/abraham] Liverani hypothesized that the members of the tribe of Raham called themselves "sons of Raham" (**Banu-Raham*), so that the name of their eponymous ancestor would have been "father of Raham" (**Abu-Raham*), that being the name of the patriarch Abraham.
[src:sparta/abraham] Finkelstein and Römer considered Abraham as ancestor who was worshiped in Hebron, with the oldest tradition of him possibly being about the altar he built in Hebron.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham is given a high position of respect in three major world faiths, Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Judaism, he is the founding father of the covenant, the special relationship between the Jewish people and God—leading to the belief that the Jews are the chosen people of God.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Christianity, Paul the Apostle taught that Abraham's faith in God, preceding receipt of the Mosaic law, made him the prototype of all believers, Jewish or gentile; and in Islam, he is seen as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad.
[src:sparta/abraham] Specifically through Jacob, renamed "Israel" in Genesis 35:10, both "a nation and a company of nations" would arise, and the promise that his descendants would become a multitude of nations is maintained through Jacob's blessing of his grandson, Ephraim, in Genesis 48:19.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Jewish tradition, Abraham is called *Avraham Avinu* (אברהם אבינו), "our father Abraham", signifying that he is both the biological progenitor of the Jews and the father of Judaism, the first Jew.
[src:sparta/abraham] His story is read in the weekly Torah reading portions, predominantly in the parashot: Lech-Lecha (לֶךְ-לְךָ), Vayeira (וַיֵּרָא), Chayei Sarah (חַיֵּי שָׂרָה), and Toledot (תּוֹלְדֹת).
[src:sparta/abraham] Hanan bar Rava taught in Abba Arikha's name that Abraham's mother was named ʾĂmatlaʾy bat Karnebo.
[src:sparta/abraham] Hiyya bar Abba taught that Abraham worked in Teraḥ's idol shop in his youth.
[src:sparta/abraham] According to the *Legends of the Jews*, God created heaven and earth for the sake of the merits of Abraham.
[src:sparta/abraham] After the biblical flood, Abraham was the only one among the pious who solemnly swore never to forsake God, studied in the house of Noah and Shem to learn about the "Ways of God", and continued the line of High Priest from Noah and Shem, assigning the office to Levi and his seed forever.
[src:sparta/abraham] Before leaving his father's land, Abraham was miraculously saved from the fiery furnace of Nimrod following his brave action of breaking the idols of the Chaldeans into pieces.
[src:sparta/abraham] During his sojourning in Canaan, Abraham was accustomed to extend hospitality to travelers and strangers and taught how to praise God also knowledge of God to those who had received his kindness.
[src:sparta/abraham] Along with Isaac and Jacob, he is the one whose name would appear united with God, as God in Judaism is called *Elohei Avraham, Elohei Yitzchak, vEilohei Ya'akov* ("God of Abraham, God of Isaac, and God of Jacob").
[src:sparta/abraham] He was also mentioned as the father of thirty nations.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Mandaeism, Abraham (Classical Mandaic: ࡀࡁࡓࡀࡄࡉࡌ, romanized: *Abrahim*) is mentioned in Book 18 of the *Right Ginza* as the patriarch of the Jewish people.
[src:sparta/abraham] Mandaeans consider Abraham to have been originally a Mandaean priest, however they differ with Abraham and Jews regarding circumcision which they consider to be bodily mutilation and therefore forbidden.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Christianity, Abraham is revered as the prophet to whom God chose to reveal himself and with whom God initiated a covenant (cf.
[src:sparta/abraham] Paul the Apostle declared that all who believe in Jesus (Christians) are "included in the seed of Abraham and are inheritors of the promise made to Abraham".
[src:sparta/abraham] Throughout history, church leaders, following Paul, have emphasized Abraham as the spiritual father of all Christians.
[src:sparta/abraham] Augustine of Hippo declared that Christians are "children (or 'seed') of Abraham by faith", Ambrose stated that "by means of their faith Christians possess the promises made to Abraham", and Martin Luther recalled Abraham as "a paradigm of the man of faith".
[src:sparta/abraham] The Roman Catholic Church, the largest Christian denomination, calls Abraham "our father in Faith" in the Eucharistic prayer of the Roman Canon, recited during the Mass.
[src:sparta/abraham] In the introduction to his 15th-century translation of the Golden Legend's account of Abraham, William Caxton noted that this patriarch's life was read in church on Quinquagesima Sunday.
[src:sparta/abraham] He is the patron saint of those in the hospitality industry.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Eastern Orthodox Church commemorates him as the "Righteous Forefather Abraham", with two feast days in its liturgical calendar.
[src:sparta/abraham] The first time is on 9 October (for those churches which follow the traditional Julian Calendar, 9 October falls on 22 October of the modern Gregorian Calendar), where he is commemorated together with his nephew "Righteous Lot".
[src:sparta/abraham] The other is on the "Sunday of the Forefathers" (two Sundays before Christmas), when he is commemorated together with other ancestors of Jesus.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham is also mentioned in the Divine Liturgy of Basil the Great, just before the Anaphora, and Abraham and Sarah are invoked in the prayers said by the priest over a newly married couple.
[src:sparta/abraham] A popular hymn sung in many English-speaking Sunday Schools by children is known as "Father Abraham" and emphasizes the patriarch as the spiritual progenitor of Christians.
[src:sparta/abraham] Islam regards *ʾIbrāhīm* (Abraham) as a link in the chain of prophets that begins with Adam and culminates in Muhammad via *ʾIsmāʿīl* (Ishmael).
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham is mentioned in 35 chapters of the Quran, more often than any other biblical personage apart from Moses.
[src:sparta/abraham] He is called both a *hanif* (monotheist) and *muslim* (one who submits), and Muslims regard him as a prophet and patriarch, the archetype of the perfect Muslim, and the revered reformer of the Kaaba in Mecca.
[src:sparta/abraham] Islamic tradition considers Abraham the first "pioneer of Islam" (which is also called *millat ʾIbrāhīm*, the 'religion of Abraham'), and that his purpose and mission throughout his life was to proclaim the oneness of God.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Islam, Abraham holds an exalted position among the major prophets and he is referred to as *Khalīlullāh*, meaning 'Friend of God'.
[src:sparta/abraham] Besides *Ishaq* and *Yaqub* (Isaac and Jacob), Abraham is among the most excellent and honorable men in the view of God.
[src:sparta/abraham] He is also mentioned in Quran as the "Father of Muslims", and is put forward as a role model for the community.
[src:sparta/abraham] The Druze regard Abraham as the third spokesman (*natiq*) after Adam and Noah, who helped transmit the foundational teachings of monotheism (*tawhid*) intended for the larger audience.
[src:sparta/abraham] He is also among the seven prophets who appeared in different periods of history according to the Druze faith.
[src:sparta/abraham] To ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, the Abraham was born to a family that was ignorant of the oneness of God.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham opposed his own people and government, and even his own kin, he rejected all their gods, and, alone and single-handed, he withstood a powerful nation.
[src:sparta/abraham] These people believed not in one God but in many gods, to whom they ascribed miracles, and hence they all rose up against Abraham.
[src:sparta/abraham] No one supported him except his nephew Lot and "one or two other individuals of no consequence".
[src:sparta/abraham] At last the intensity of his enemies' opposition obliged him, utterly wronged, to forsake his native land.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham then came to "these regions", that is, to the Holy Land.
[src:sparta/abraham] To Bahá'u'lláh, the "Voice of God" commanded Abraham to offer up Ishmael as a sacrifice, so that his steadfastness in the faith of God and his detachment from all else but him may be demonstrated unto men.
[src:sparta/abraham] The purpose of God, moreover, was to sacrifice him as a ransom for the sins and iniquities of all the peoples of the earth.
[src:sparta/abraham] In the Baháʼí texts, like the Islamic texts, Abraham is often referred to as "the Friend of God".
[src:sparta/abraham] 'Abdu'l-Bahá described Abraham as the founder of monotheism.
[src:sparta/abraham] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá also suggested the "holy manifestations who have been the sources or founders of the various religious systems" were united and agreed in purpose and teaching, and the Abraham, Moses, Zoroaster, the Buddha, Jesus, Muhammad, the Báb and Bahá'u'lláh are one in "spirit and reality".
[src:sparta/abraham] Paintings on the life of Abraham tend to focus on only a few incidents: the sacrifice of Isaac; meeting Melchizedek; entertaining the three angels; Hagar in the desert; and a few others.
[src:sparta/abraham] Additionally, Martin O'Kane, a professor of Biblical Studies, writes that the parable of Lazarus resting in the "Bosom of Abraham", as described in the Gospel of Luke, became an iconic image in Christian works.
[src:sparta/abraham] According to O'Kane, artists often chose to divert from the common literary portrayal of Lazarus sitting next to Abraham at a banquet in Heaven and instead focus on the "somewhat incongruous notion of Abraham, the most venerated of patriarchs, holding a naked and vulnerable child in his bosom".
[src:sparta/abraham] Several artists have been inspired by the life of Abraham, including Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528), Caravaggio (1573–1610), Donatello, Raphael, Philip van Dyck (Dutch painter, 1680–1753), and Claude Lorrain (French painter, 1600–1682).
[src:sparta/abraham] The Sarcophagus of Junius Bassus depicts a set of biblical stories, including Abraham about to sacrifice Isaac.
[src:sparta/abraham] These sculpted scenes are on the outside of a marble Early Christian sarcophagus used for the burial of Junius Bassus.
[src:sparta/abraham] This sarcophagus has been described as "probably the single most famous piece of early Christian relief sculpture." The sarcophagus was originally placed in or under Old St.
[src:sparta/abraham] Peter's Basilica, was rediscovered in 1597, and is now below the modern basilica in the Museo Storico del Tesoro della Basilica di San Pietro (Museum of St.
[src:sparta/abraham] The base is approximately 4 ft × 8 ft × 4 ft (1.2 m × 2.4 m × 1.2 m).
[src:sparta/abraham] George Segal created figural sculptures by molding plastered gauze strips over live models in his 1987 work *Abraham's Farewell to Ishmael*.
[src:sparta/abraham] The human condition was central to his concerns, and Segal used the Old Testament as a source for his imagery.
[src:sparta/abraham] This sculpture depicts the dilemma faced by Abraham when Sarah demanded that he expel Hagar and Ishmael.
[src:sparta/abraham] In the sculpture, the father's tenderness, Sarah's rage, and Hagar's resigned acceptance portray a range of human emotions.
[src:sparta/abraham] The sculpture was donated to the Miami Art Museum after the artist's death in 2000.
[src:sparta/abraham] Abraham can sometimes be identified by the context of the image – the meeting with Melchizedek, the three visitors, or the sacrifice of Isaac.
[src:sparta/abraham] In solo portraits a sword or knife may be used as his accessory, as in this statue by Giovanni Maria Morlaiter or this painting by Lorenzo Monaco.
[src:sparta/abraham] As early as the beginning of the 3rd century, Christian art followed Christian typology in making the sacrifice of Isaac a foreshadowing of Christ's sacrifice on the cross, and its memorial in the sacrifice of the Mass.
[src:sparta/abraham] See for example this 11th-century Christian altar engraved with Abraham's and other sacrifices taken to prefigure that of Christ in the Eucharist.
[src:sparta/abraham] Some early Christian writers interpreted the three visitors as the triune God.
[src:sparta/abraham] Thus in Santa Maria Maggiore, Rome, a 5th-century mosaic portrays only the visitors against a gold ground and puts semitransparent copies of them in the "heavenly" space above the scene.
[src:sparta/abraham] In Eastern Orthodox art, the visit is the chief means by which the Trinity is pictured (example).
[src:sparta/abraham] Some images do not include Abraham and Sarah, like Andrei Rublev's *Trinity*, which shows only the three visitors as beardless youths at a table.
[src:sparta/abraham] In 1681, Marc-Antoine Charpentier released a Dramatic motet (Oratorio), **Sacrificim Abrahae** H.402 – 402 a – 402 b, for soloists, chorus, doubling instruments and continuo.
[src:sparta/abraham] Sébastien de Brossard composed a cantata **Abraham ou le sacrifice d'Isaac** between 1703 and 1708.
[src:sparta/abraham] In 1994, Steve Reich released an opera named *The Cave*.
[src:sparta/abraham] The title refers to the Cave of the Patriarchs.
[src:sparta/abraham] The narrative of the opera is based on the story of Abraham, and his immediate family, as it is recounted in religious texts, and understood by individuals from different cultures and religious traditions.
[src:sparta/abraham] The eponymous track on Bob Dylan's 1965 album *Highway 61 Revisited* contains five stanzas, with someone in each describing an unusual problem that is ultimately resolved on Highway 61.
[src:sparta/abraham] In the first stanza, God tells Abraham to "kill me a son".
[src:sparta/abraham] God wants the killing done on Highway 61.
[src:sparta/abraham] *Abram*, the birth name of Abraham, is also the name of Dylan's father.
[src:sparta/abraham] In 2004, *Rolling Stone* magazine ranked "Highway 61 Revisited" at number 364 in their 500 Greatest Songs of All Time.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The **Acarnanian League** (Ancient Greek: τὸ κοινὸν τῶν Ἁκαρνάνων, *to koinon tōn Akarnanōn*) was the tribal confederation, and later a fully-fledged federation (*koinon*), of the Acarnanians in Classical, Hellenistic, and early Roman-era Greece.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The League existed since the 5th century BC.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] It was at the time not a fully-fledged federation (*sympoliteia*) as elsewhere in Greece, but a loose confederation of the Acarnanian cities.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] An assembly of representatives met at Stratos, having also the power of negotiating treaties with other states, a supreme court existed at Olpae (in common with the Amphilochians), and there was a common coinage and cult, but no federal officials and no common foreign policy.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanians agreed to provide 2,000 hoplites in the common struggle against Philip II of Macedon, but as the latter occupied Ambracia, only a handful volunteers participated alongside the southern Greek city-states in the Battle of Chaeronea.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] As a result, the leaders of the independence faction were banished, and the League became a member of the League of Corinth organized by Philip.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] During Alexander the Great's campaign in Asia, the Aetolians seized the town of Oiniadai from the League.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] With the exception of Alyzia, the Acarnanians remained largely uninvolved in the struggles that followed the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BCE, but in 314 BCE Cassander arrived in Acarnania and reorganized the League on a truly federal basis.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The island of Leucas joined the League soon after, following the eviction of its Macedonian garrison.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League was a member of the Hellenic League organized by Demetrius Poliorcetes, and then became subject to King Pyrrhus of Epirus.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] 270 BCE, the Acarnanians and Aetolians settled their differences, agreeing on the Acheloos River as their mutual border, and concluded a perpetual alliance.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The treaty specified the obligations of mutual military assistance, and the two leagues assured each other the rights of *epigamia*, citizenship, and acquisition of property.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] This treaty records seven *strategoi* (one each from Oiniadai, Derion, Stratos, Phoitia, Thyrreion, Anaktorion and Leucas), a hipparch (from Oiniadai), a foreign secretary (from Oiniadai), and a treasurer (from Stratos).
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The frequent occurrence of officials indicates that at the time it was the most important city of the League.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] According to Polybius, however, soon after the Aetolians allied themselves with Pyrrhus' son.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Alexander II of Epirus, and invaded Acarnania, dividing the country between them: the northern part with Leucas went to Epirus, and the south was incorporated into the Aetolian League.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Following the extinction of the Aeacid dynasty in Epirus, in 230 BCE the Acarnanian League was reconstituted in the northern, former Epirote part of the country.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Leucas was its capital, and only Anaktorion, Palairos, Thyrreion, and Medion were members.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Allied with the Illyrians, and then with the Macedonians and the Achaean League, in the Social War (220–217 BCE) the Acarnanians were able to recover Phoitia and Oiniadai.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] This success did not last long: in the First Macedonian War (214–205 BCE), Oiniadai was lost again, and in the Second Macedonian War (200–197 BCE) the Acarnanians were forced to capitulate to the Roman Republic, who however left them in their possessions and free to govern themselves.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Oiniadai was returned after the Roman–Seleucid War.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] Despite their steadfast loyalty to Rome, the League lost Leucas after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE), as it became an autonomous state, but Thyrreion became a member.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League continued to exist even after the final establishment of Roman power over Greece in 146 BCE.
[src:sparta/acarnanian-league] It was only after the Battle of Actium in 31 BCE that the League was incorporated into the Roman province of Achaea.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The **Achaean League** (Ancient Greek: Κοινὸν τῶν Ἀχαιῶν, romanized: *Koinon ton Akhaion*, lit.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] 'League of Achaeans') was a Hellenistic-era confederation of Greek city-states on the northern and central Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The league was named after the region of Achaea in the northwestern Peloponnese, which formed its original core.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The first league was formed in the fifth century BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Although the first Achaean League is much less well documented than its later revival, it maintained a recognizable federal structure through the early Hellenistic period, but later fell into a period of dormancy under growing Macedonian influence.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The more famous second Achaean League was established in 280 BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] It allied with Antigonid Macedon at the Cleomenean War, Social War and First Macedonian War against the Aetolian League and Sparta.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Its most successful leader was Philopoemen who forced Sparta to join the League.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The league allied with the Roman Republic during the Second Macedonian War and the Aetolian War.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The Achaean War led to the League's conquest and dissolution by the Romans in 146 BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The League represents the most successful attempt by the Greek city-states to develop a form of federalism, which balanced the need for collective action with the desire for local autonomy.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Through the writings of the Achaean historian and statesman Polybius, this structure has had an influence on the constitution of the United States and other modern federal states.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The first Achaean League became active in the fifth century in the northwestern Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Its earliest organizational structure remains partly obscure, but new evidence has illuminated aspects of its government.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] A fragmentary inscription discovered at Aegium, dating to the fourth or possibly the very beginning of the third century BC, attests to a developed federal system that included a *boule* (federal council) and a board of *damiourgoi* (federal magistrates).
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The ancient capital of the league was Helike, but after the catastrophic destruction of that city by an earthquake and tsunami in 373 BC, Aegium subsequently assumed that role.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Xenophon's *Hellenica* reports that Achaea underwent a democratic revolution in 367 and the previous ruling class was exiled.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Although it was once widely claimed that Alexander the Great dissolved the Achaean League in 324 BC, the passage in Hypereides (*Against Demosthenes* 18) supposed to reference such a dissolution is now widely understood to be too ambiguous to support that interpretation.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The idea is further undermined by the continued political activity of Achaea and Arcadia during the Lamian War, when they refused to join the Greeks while Boeotia did support Antipater.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The league continued to exist into the early Hellenistic period and is attested in 302 BC, when the Achaeans were listed among the members of the League of Corinth revived by Demetrius Poliorcetes.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In the years following, Macedonian influence intensified in some Achaean cities while others became ruled by tyrants.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This period of increasing external control appears to have been linked to Demetrius’ change in policy, signalled by his capture and fortification of Athens in 294 BC, with the planting of garrisons in Achaean cities likely occurring shortly thereafter.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Polybius records that during this time, tyrannies were established in cities such as Ceryneia and Bura, and a garrison was stationed at Aegium.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Despite this interference, there is no indication that the Achaean League was formally dissolved.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Historian Jakob Larsen suggests that the confederacy's federal institutions effectively ceased to operate because so many of its member cities were under external control.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This state of suspension allowed the league to resume its functions later without the need for significant constitutional changes, suggesting that some mutual understanding among the cities facilitated its reactivation when conditions allowed.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The regional Achaean League was revived in 281/0 BC by the communities of Dyme, Patrae, Pharae and Tritaea, joined in 275 by Aegium, which controlled the important sanctuary of Zeus Homarios.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The league grew quickly to include the entire Achaean heartland, and after a decade it had ten or eleven members.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The key moment for the League's transformation into a major power came in 251, when Aratus, the exiled son of a former magistrate of Sicyon, overthrew the tyranny in his native city and brought it into the Achaean League.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Since the Sicyonians were of Dorian and Ionian origin, their inclusion opened the League for other national elements.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus, then only twenty years old, rapidly became the leading politician of the League.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In the thirty two years between 245 and his death in 213, Aratus would hold the office of general a total of sixteen times.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] At this time, Central Greece and the Peloponnese were dominated by the Macedonian Kingdom of Antigonus II Gonatas who maintained garrisons at key strategic points such as Chalcis, Piraeus and Acrocorinth, the so-called "fetters of Greece".
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In other cities of the Peloponnese, namely Argos, Orchomenus, and Megalopolis, Antigonus had installed friendly rulers who were perceived as tyrants by the Achaeans.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus, whose father had been killed by one, called for the liberation of these cities and secured financial support for the League from Ptolemy II of Egypt, an enemy of the Antigonids.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] He then used the money to challenge the Macedonian hold on the Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus' greatest success came when he captured Corinth and the fortress of Acrocorinth in 243 BC in a daring night attack.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This effectively blocked Macedonian access to the Peloponnese by land, isolating their allies at Megalopolis and Argos.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In light of this success, a number of Greek communities, including Epidaurus and Megara joined the League and Ptolemy III increased Egypt's support for the Achaeans, being elected as the League's *hegemon* (leader) in return.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Antigonus Gonatas finally made peace with the Achaean League in a treaty of 240 BC, ceding the territories that he had lost in Greece.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The increased size of the league meant a bigger citizen army and more wealth, which was used to hire mercenaries, but it also led to hostility from the remaining independent Greek states, especially Elis, the Aetolian League and Sparta, which perceived the Achaeans as a threat.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Corinth was followed by Megalopolis in 235 BC and Argos in 229 BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] However the league soon ran into difficulties with the revived Sparta of Cleomenes III.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus was forced to call in the aid of the Macedonian King, Antigonus III Doson, who defeated Cleomenes at Sellasia.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Antigonus Doson re-established Macedonian control over much of the region.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In 220 BC, the Achaean League entered into a war against the Aetolian League, which was called the "Social War".
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The young king Philip V of Macedon sided with the Achaeans and called for a Panhellenic conference in Corinth, where the Aetolian aggression was condemned.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] After Aratus's death, however, the League joined Rome in the Second Macedonian War (200–196 BC), which broke Macedonian power in mainland Greece.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The Achaean League was one of the main beneficiaries.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Under the leadership of Philopoemen, the League was able to finally defeat a heavily weakened Sparta and take control of the entire Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The League's dominance was not to last long, however.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In 146 BC, the league's relations with Rome completely collapsed, leading to the Achaean War.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The Romans under Lucius Mummius defeated the Achaeans at the Battle of Corinth, razed Corinth and dissolved the League, finally putting an end to the independence of Ancient Greece from external rule and ushering in the Roman era.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Griffith has written that Achaean War was "a hopeless enterprise for the Achaeans, badly led and backed by no adequate reserves of money or men." Lucius Mummius received the agnomen *Achaicus* ("conqueror of Achaea") for his role.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The original name Koinon of Achaeans (Achaean League) continues to exist in epigraphy, denoting either the previous Peloponnesian members (see koinon of Free Laconians) or the whole of Roman Achaea.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] 120 BC Achaeans of cities in the Peloponnese dedicated an honorary inscription to Olympian Zeus, after a military expedition with Gnaeus Domitius against the Galatians in Gallia Transalpina.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The government of the league consisted of an assembly of citizens, a smaller council, and a *strategos* (general).
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The *strategos* (general) controlled the league's military forces.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Originally, two *strategoi* held office simultaneously, but from 251, there was only one, who was elected annually by the assembly.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Until 217 the *strategos* entered office in May; afterwards he assumed power at the beginning of winter.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Individuals could hold the office more than once (and frequently did so), but not in consecutive years.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The general was assisted in his duties by a board of ten *demiourgoi*, a secretary, a *hipparch* (cavalry commander), a *navarch* (admiral), and *hypostrategoi* (sub-generals commanding in military districts).
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The office of *Hegemon* (leader) was given to various Antigonid and Ptolemaic kings at various points in Achaean history.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Ostensibly, the *hegemon* had ultimate command on land and sea, but in fact the office seems to have been an honorary position which obliged the holder to contribute money to the League and support the League's military ventures.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Ultimate decision-making power rested with the assembly (*synodos*), which was held at Aegium four times a year.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] All male citizens of communities belonging to the League were entitled to attend.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Alongside the assembly there was a council (*boule*), which was open to citizen men over thirty years old.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Special meetings (*synkletoi*) had to be called in order for the league to declare war, form an alliance, or receive official communications from the Macedonian king or (later) the Roman Republic.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The league was ostensibly a democracy, but control seems to have consistently rested with a small elite group who monopolised the generalship and other official positions.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Given the difficulty of travelling to Aegium, assemblies were probably dominated by the wealthy.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The Achaean army was an army of the traditional *hoplite* type.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] From the 270s onwards however, much like the rest of Greece, the emergence of the shield known as the *thyreos* was incorporated into Greek warfare and a new type of troop was developed.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Reforming their troops into *thyreophoroi*, the Achaean army was now composed of light troops.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The *thyreophoroi* were a mixture of evolved *peltasts* and light *hoplites*, carrying the *thureos* shield, a thrusting spear and javelins.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Plutarch says that they could be effective at a distance, but in close combat the narrow *thureos* shield disadvantaged them.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] He also says that their formation was ineffective, because it lacked inter-locked shields or a 'leveled line of spears'.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus, one of the major Achaean *strategoi* (generals) and statesmen was known for his use of light forces for irregular operations, a type of warfare suited to the *thyreophoroi* but not suited to operations in the open field.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The League in 217 decided to maintain a standing force of 8,000 mercenary foot and 500 mercenary cavalry, added to a picked citizen force of 3,000 infantry and 300 cavalry, of which 500 foot and 50 horse would come from Argos and the same amount from Megalopolis.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Aratus also obtained 500 foot and 50 horse each from Taurion and the Messenians for defence of parts of the League open to attack via Laconia.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The citizen infantry would have been armed as *thyreophoroi*, apart from the citizen light troops who would have been archers and slingers etc.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This picked citizen force may well have existed before these so-called reforms, at least on an official basis, as we know of a similar elite force of the same size at the Battle of Sellasia in 222.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] However, it was the Achaean general Philopoemen in 208 who changed the Achaean fighting style and weaponry to the Macedonian fashion.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] According to Plutarch, Philopoemen 'persuaded them to adopt long pike and heavy shield instead of spear and buckler, to protect their bodies with helmets and breastplates and greaves, and to practice stationary and steadfast fighting instead of the nimble movements of light-armed troops'.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] These 'reforms' were not necessarily new to some of the constituent cities of the League, as the city of Megalopolis had been given bronze shields and armed in the Macedonian fashion by Antigonus Doson for the Sellasia campaign many years before.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Philopoemen then trained the new army how to fight with the new weapons and tactics and how to co-ordinate them with a new mercenary corps that was hired.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] He spent nearly 8 months of his term as *strategos* visiting, training and advising cities in this capacity.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] At the Battle of Mantinea in 207 BC the Achaean phalanx was positioned with intervals between the companies with lighter troops.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This was a major attempt by Philopoemen to increase the flexibility of his phalanx.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] He may have picked up this tactic too from his experience at the Battle of Sellasia, where the phalanx of Antigonus Doson was also divided up with light/medium troops in between them.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] As well as reforming and re-organizing the infantry, Philopoemen also reformed the citizen cavalry.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The cavalry was recruited, much like in other Greek states, from the rich and noble classes.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Philopoemen organized the cavalry in *lochoi*, which usually in ancient military treatises means 'files', most probably of 8 men, grouped into *dilochiai*, a formation of double-files of 16 and so forth.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] However, by the time of the Achaean War in 146 BC, the League's army had decreased in strength and efficiency.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The League was even reduced to freeing and arming 12,000 slaves.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This was probably due to the 2nd century BC decline in population.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] This may well account for the increased hiring of mercenaries, especially Cretans and Thracians.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The below are the original Peloponnesian members, except the ancient regions of Sparta, Elis and Messenia.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Later Hypana in Elis, Corone, Messene, Sparta and Pagae in Attica were joined by conquest.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] In 223 BC, Megara in Attica deserted the Achaean League and joined the Boeotian Confederacy.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Besides many city-states on the Mainland joining the Achaean Federation, certain Mediterranean island city-states also became part of the federation.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] For example, Kydonia on Crete joined at some time after 219 BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The city of Helike had been an important member of the first Achaean League, but sank into the sea following a disastrous earthquake in 373 BC.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The town of Olenus, also one of the twelve members of the first Achaean League, had been abandoned before 280 BC, but was sometimes counted as though still extant.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] The dates in brackets indicate the year of first adhesion.
[src:sparta/achaean-league] Some cities had periods of separation or foreign occupation and later joined again.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta was recognised as the leading force of the unified Greek military during the Greco-Persian Wars, in an alliance with the competing and rising naval power of Athens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartan army was crucial in the battles of Thermopylae and Plataea under the leadership of Leonidas and Pausanias respectively.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta led the Peloponnesian League against the Athenian empire during the Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC), from which it emerged victorious after Lysander's victory at the naval Battle of Aegospotami.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] A short period of Spartan hegemony followed, when Spartan armies led by Agesilaus II even invaded the western Anatolian satrapies of the Achaemenid empire.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The city recovered some autonomy after the Roman conquest of Greece in 146 BC and became a tourist destination during the Roman era, restoring some measure of prosperity.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, Sparta was sacked in 396 AD by the Visigothic king Alaric, and underwent a long period of decline into the medieval period, when much of its population relocated to Mystras.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Modern Sparta is a provincial town and the seat of the Laconia regional administration.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta was unique in ancient Greece for its social system and constitution, which were supposedly introduced by the semi-mythical lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan society was exceptionally militarised, focusing the entire attention of the Spartiate class on military training and physical development to the point of legally barring them from productive economic activity.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The inhabitants of Sparta were rigidly stratified into Spartiates (citizens with full rights), mothakes and perioikoi (free non-citizens), and helots (state-owned enslaved non-Spartan locals), with helots making up the vast majority of the population; social mobility was nearly nonexistent.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartiate men underwent the harsh *agoge* training regimen, and Spartan phalanx units were widely considered to be among the best in battle, though this was as much a matter of propaganda as battlefield prowess.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Free Spartiate women enjoyed somewhat greater legal rights than elsewhere in classical antiquity, though helots suffered exceptionally harsh treatment at the hands of the Spartiates (particularly the Crypteia), causing repeated revolts.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta was a subject of fascination in its own day, as well as in later Western culture following the revival of classical learning.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The admiration of Sparta is known as Laconophilia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The ancient Greeks used one of three words to refer to the Spartan city-state and its location.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] First, "Sparta" refers primarily to the main cluster of settlements in the valley of the Eurotas River.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The second word, "Lacedaemon" (Λακεδαίμων), was often used as an adjective and is the name referenced in the works of Homer and the historians Herodotus and Thucydides.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The third term, "Laconice" (Λακωνική), referred to the immediate area around the town of Sparta, the plateau east of the Taygetos mountains, and sometimes to all the regions under direct Spartan control, including Messenia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The earliest attested term referring to Lacedaemon is the Mycenaean Greek 𐀨𐀐𐀅𐀖𐀛𐀍, *ra-ke-da-mi-ni-jo*, "Lakedaimonian", written in Linear B syllabic script, the equivalent of the later Greek Λακεδαιμόνιος, *Lakedaimonios* (Latin: *Lacedaemonius*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Herodotus seems to use "Lacedaemon" for the Mycenaean Greek citadel at Therapne, in contrast to the lower town of Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This term could be used synonymously with Sparta, but typically it denoted the region in which the city was located.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In Homer it is typically combined with epithets of the countryside: wide, lovely, shining and most often hollow and broken (full of ravines), suggesting the Eurotas Valley.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] "Sparta" on the other hand is described as "the country of lovely women", an epithet for people.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The residents of Sparta were often called Lacedaemonians.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This epithet utilised the plural of the adjective Lacedaemonius (Greek: Λακεδαιμόνιοι; Latin: *Lacedaemonii*, but also *Lacedaemones*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The ancients sometimes used a back-formation, referring to the land of Lacedaemon as *Lacedaemonian country*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As most words for "country" were feminine, the adjective was in the feminine: *Lacedaemonia* (Λακεδαιμονία, *Lakedaimonia*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Eventually, the adjective came to be used alone.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] "Lacedaemonia" was not in general use during the classical period and before.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] It does occur in Greek as an equivalent of Laconia and Messenia during the Roman and early Byzantine periods, mostly in ethnographers and lexica of place names.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] For example, Hesychius of Alexandria's *Lexicon* (5th century AD) defines Agiadae as a "place in Lacedaemonia" named after Agis.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The actual transition may be captured by Isidore of Seville's *Etymologiae* (7th century AD), an etymological dictionary.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Isidore relied heavily on Orosius's *Historiarum Adversum Paganos* (5th century AD) and Eusebius of Caesarea's *Chronicon* (early 5th century AD), as did Orosius.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The latter defines Sparta to be *Lacedaemonia Civitas*, but Isidore defines Lacedaemonia as founded by Lacedaemon, son of Semele, which is consistent with Eusebius's explanation.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] There is a rare use, perhaps the earliest of "Lacedaemonia", in Diodorus Siculus's *The Library of History*, but probably with Χώρα (*chōra*, "country") suppressed.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Lakedaimona was until 2006 the name of a province in the modern Greek prefecture of Laconia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta is located in the region of Laconia, in the south-eastern Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Ancient Sparta was built on the banks of the Eurotas, the largest river of Laconia, which provided it with a source of fresh water.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Eurotas valley was a natural fortress, bounded to the west by Mt.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Taygetus (2,407 m) and to the east by Mt.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] To the north, Laconia is separated from Arcadia by hilly uplands reaching 1000 m in altitude.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These natural defences worked to Sparta's advantage and protected it from sacking and invasion.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Though landlocked, Sparta had a vassal harbour, Gytheio, on the Laconian Gulf.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Lacedaemon (Greek: Λακεδαίμων) was a mythical king of Laconia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The son of Zeus by the nymph Taygete, he married Sparta, the daughter of Eurotas, by whom he became the father of Amyclas, Eurydice, and Asine.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As king, he named his country after himself and the city after his wife.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] He was believed to have built the sanctuary of the Charites, which stood between Sparta and Amyclae, and to have given to those divinities the names of Cleta and Phaenna.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] A shrine was erected to him in the neighbourhood of Therapne.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Tyrtaeus, an archaic era Spartan writer, is the earliest source to connect the origin myth of the Spartans to the lineage of the hero Heracles; later authors, such as Diodorus Siculus, Herodotus, and Apollodorus, also made mention of Spartans understanding themselves to be descendants of Heracles.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The remaining archaeological wealth consisted of inscriptions, sculptures, and other objects collected in the local museum, founded by Stamatakis in 1872 and enlarged in 1907.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Partial excavation of the round building was undertaken in 1892 and 1893 by the American School at Athens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The structure has been since found to be a semicircular retaining wall of Hellenic origin that was partly restored during the Roman period.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 1904, the British School at Athens began a thorough exploration of Laconia, and in the following year excavations were made at Thalamae, Geronthrae, and Angelona near Monemvasia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 1906, excavations began in Sparta itself.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] A "small circus" (as described by Leake) proved to be a theatre-like building constructed soon after 200 AD around the altar and in front of the Temple of Artemis Orthia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] It is believed that musical and gymnastic contests took place here, as well as the famous flogging ordeal administered to Spartan boys (*diamastigosis*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The temple, which can be dated to the 2nd century BC, rests on the foundation of an older temple of the 6th century, and close beside it were found the remains of a yet earlier temple, dating from the 9th or even the 10th century.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The votive offerings in clay, amber, bronze, ivory and lead dating from the 9th to the 4th centuries BC, which were found in great profusion within the precinct range, supply invaluable information about early Spartan art.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 1907, the location of the sanctuary of Athena "of the Brazen House" (Χαλκίοικος, Chalkioikos) was determined to be on the acropolis immediately above the theatre.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Though the actual temple is almost completely destroyed, the site has produced the longest extant archaic inscription in Laconia, numerous bronze nails and plates, and a considerable number of votive offerings.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The city wall, built in successive stages from the 4th to the 2nd century, was traced for a great part of its circuit, which measured 48 stades or nearly 10 km (6 miles) (Polyb.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The late Roman wall enclosing the acropolis, part of which probably dates from the years following the Gothic raid of 262 AD, was also investigated.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Besides the actual buildings discovered, a number of points were situated and mapped in a general study of Spartan topography, based upon the description of Pausanias.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In terms of domestic archaeology, little is known about Spartan houses and villages before the Archaic period, but the best evidence comes from excavations at Nichoria in Messenia where postholes have been found.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These villages were open and consisted of small and simple houses built with stone foundations and clay walls.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Built around the early 8th century BC, the Spartans believed it had been the former residence of Menelaus.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 1970, the British School in Athens started excavations around the Menelaion in an attempt to locate Mycenaean remains in the area.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] There are remains of three Mycenaean mansions which were likely destroyed by earthquakes or fire.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The offerings dedicated to Helen and Menelaus made during the Classical period were also found at the site.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Excavations made from the early 1990s to the present suggest that the area around the Menelaion in the southern part of the Eurotas valley seems to have been the centre of Mycenaean Laconia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Mycenaean settlement was roughly triangular in shape, with its apex pointed towards the north.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Its area was approximately equal to that of the "newer" Sparta, but denudation has wreaked havoc with its buildings and nothing is left of its original structures save for ruined foundations and broken potsherds.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The prehistory of Sparta is difficult to reconstruct because the literary evidence was written far later than the events it describes and is distorted by oral tradition.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The earliest certain evidence of human settlement in the region of Sparta consists of pottery dating from the Middle Neolithic period, found in the vicinity of Kouphovouno some two kilometres (1.2 miles) south-southwest of Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This civilisation seems to have fallen into decline by the late Bronze Age, when, according to Herodotus, Macedonian tribes from the north (called Dorians by those they conquered) marched into the Peloponnese and, subjugating the local tribes, settled there.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Dorians seem to have set about expanding the frontiers of Spartan territory almost before they had established their own state.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] They fought against the Argive Dorians to the east and southeast, and also the Arcadian Achaeans to the northwest.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The evidence suggests that Sparta, relatively inaccessible because of the topography of the Taygetan plain, was secure from early on: it was never fortified.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Nothing distinctive in the archaeology of the Eurotas River Valley identifies the Dorians or the Dorian Spartan state.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The prehistory of the Neolithic, the Bronze Age and the Dark Age (the Early Iron Age) at this moment must be treated apart from the stream of Dorian Spartan history.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The legendary period of Spartan history is believed to fall into the Dark Age.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] It treats the mythic heroes such as the Heraclids and the Perseids, offering a view of the occupation of the Peloponnesus that contains both fantastic and possibly historical elements.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The subsequent proto-historic period, combining both legend and historical fragments, offers the first credible history.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Between the 8th and 7th centuries BC the Spartans experienced a period of lawlessness and civil strife, later attested by both Herodotus and Thucydides.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As a result, they carried out a series of political and social reforms of their own society which they later attributed to a semi-mythical lawgiver, Lycurgus.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Several writers throughout antiquity, including Herodotus, Xenophon, and Plutarch have attempted to explain Spartan exceptionalism as a result of the so-called Lycurgan Reforms.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In the Second Messenian War, Sparta established itself as a local power in the Peloponnesus and the rest of Greece.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] During the following centuries, Sparta's reputation as a land-fighting force was unequalled.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] At its peak around 500 BC, Sparta had some 20,000–35,000 citizens, plus numerous helots and perioikoi.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The likely total of 40,000–50,000 made Sparta one of the larger Greek city-states; however, according to Thucydides, the population of Athens in 431 BC was 360,000–610,000, making it much larger.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 480 BC, a small force led by King Leonidas (about 300 full Spartiates, 700 Thespians, and 400 Thebans, although these numbers were lessened by earlier casualties) made a legendary last stand at the Battle of Thermopylae against the massive Persian army, led by Xerxes.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartans received advance warning of the Persian invasion from their deposed king Demaratus, which prompted them to consult the Delphic oracle.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] According to Herodotus, the Pythia proclaimed that either one of the kings of Sparta had to die or Sparta would be destroyed.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This prophecy was fulfilled after king Leonidas died in the battle.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The superior weaponry, strategy, and bronze armour of the Greek hoplites and their phalanx fighting formation again proved their worth one year later when Sparta assembled its full strength and led a Greek alliance against the Persians at the Battle of Plataea in 479 BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The decisive Greek victory at Plataea put an end to the Greco-Persian War along with Persian ambitions to expand into Europe.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Even though this war was won by a pan-Greek army, credit was given to Sparta, who besides providing the leading forces at Thermopylae and Plataea, had been the leader of the entire Greek expedition.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 464 BC, a violent earthquake occurred along the Sparta faultline destroying much of what was Sparta and many other city-states in ancient Greece.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This earthquake is marked by scholars as one of the key events that led to the First Peloponnesian War.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In later Classical times, Sparta along with Athens, Thebes, and Persia were the main powers fighting for supremacy in the northeastern Mediterranean.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In the course of the Peloponnesian War, Sparta, a traditional land power, acquired a navy which managed to overpower the previously dominant flotilla of Athens, ending the Athenian Empire.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] At the peak of its power in the early 4th century BC, Sparta had subdued many of the main Greek states and even invaded the Persian provinces in Anatolia (modern day Turkey), a period known as the Spartan hegemony.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] During the Corinthian War, Sparta faced a coalition of the leading Greek states: Thebes, Athens, Corinth, and Argos.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The alliance was initially backed by Persia, which feared further Spartan expansion into Asia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta achieved a series of land victories, but many of her ships were destroyed at the Battle of Cnidus by a Greek-Phoenician mercenary fleet that Persia had provided to Athens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The event severely damaged Sparta's naval power but did not end its aspirations of invading further into Persia, until Conon the Athenian ravaged the Spartan coastline and provoked the old Spartan fear of a helot revolt.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] After a few more years of fighting, in 387 BC the Peace of Antalcidas was established, according to which all Greek cities of Ionia would return to Persian control, and Persia's Asian border would be free of the Spartan threat.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The effects of the war were to reaffirm Persia's ability to interfere successfully in Greek politics and to affirm Sparta's weakened hegemonic position in the Greek political system.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta suffered a severe military defeat to Epaminondas of Thebes at the Battle of Leuctra.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As Spartan citizenship was inherited by blood, Sparta increasingly faced a helot population that vastly outnumbered its citizens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The alarming decline of Spartan citizens was commented on by Aristotle.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta never fully recovered from its losses at Leuctra in 371 BC and the subsequent helot revolts.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 338 BC, Philip II invaded and devastated much of Laconia, turning the Spartans out, though he did not seize Sparta itself.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Even during its decline, Sparta never forgot its claim to be the "defender of Hellenism" and its Laconic wit.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] An anecdote has it that when Philip II sent a message to Sparta saying "If I invade Laconia, I shall turn you out.", the Spartans responded with the single, terse reply: αἴκα, "if".
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] When Philip created the League of Corinth on the pretext of unifying Greece against Persia, the Spartans chose not to join, since they had no interest in joining a pan-Greek expedition unless it were under Spartan leadership.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Thus, upon defeating the Persians at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander the Great sent to Athens 300 suits of Persian armour with the following inscription: "Alexander, son of Philip, and all the Greeks except the Spartans, give these offerings taken from the foreigners who live in Asia".
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartan king Agis III sent a force to Crete in 333 BC to secure the island for the Persian interest.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Agis next took action against Macedon by laying siege to Megalopolis in 331 BC, while Alexander campaigned against the Persians in Asia as leader of the Hellenic league.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, a large Macedonian army under general Antipater marched to its relief and defeated the Spartan-led force in a pitched battle.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] More than 5,300 of the Spartans and their allies were killed in battle, and 3,500 of Antipater's troops.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Agis, now wounded and unable to stand, ordered his men to leave him behind to face the advancing Macedonian army so that he could buy them time to retreat.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] On his knees, the Spartan king slew several enemy soldiers before being finally killed by a javelin.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Alexander was merciful, and he only forced the Spartans to join the League of Corinth, which they had previously refused.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] After the Diadochi Wars, Sparta continued to be one of the Peloponesian powers until its eventual loss of independence in 192 BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 272 BC Pyrrhus of Epirus failed to besiege Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Cleomenes III allied with the Ptolemaic kingdom and tried to make Sparta the dominant power of the Peloponnese against the Achaean League with initial successes but he was finally defeated in 222 BC at the battle of Sellasia from a Macedonian-Achaean alliance under Antigonus Doson.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] During the First Macedonian War, Sparta was an ally of the Roman Republic.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan political independence was put to an end when it was eventually forced into the Achaean League by Philopoemen, after its defeat in the decisive Laconian War by a coalition of other Greek city-states and Rome, and the resultant overthrow of its final king Nabis, in 192 BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta played no active part in the Achaean War in 146 BC when the Achaean League was defeated by the Roman general Lucius Mummius.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Subsequently, Sparta became a free city under Roman rule, some of the institutions of Lycurgus were restored, and the city became a tourist attraction for the Roman elite who came to observe exotic Spartan customs.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 214 AD, Roman emperor Caracalla, in his preparation for his campaign against Parthia, recruited a 500-man Spartan cohort (*lokhos*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Herodian described this unit as a *phalanx*, implying it fought like the old Spartans as hoplites, or even as a Macedonian phalanx.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Despite this, a gravestone of a fallen legionary named Marcus Aurelius Alexys shows him lightly armed, with a pilos-like cap and a wooden club.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The unit was presumably discharged in 217 after Caracalla was assassinated.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The letters are reproduced in a variant form by Josephus.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartans long spurned the idea of building a defensive wall around their city, believing they made the city's men soft in terms of their warrior abilities.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] A wall was finally erected after 184 BCE, after the peak of the city-state's power had come and gone.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In 396 AD, Sparta was sacked by Visigoths under Alaric I.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] According to Byzantine sources, some parts of the Laconian region remained pagan until well into the 10th century.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Tsakonian language still spoken in Tsakonia is the only surviving descendant of the ancient Doric language.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In the Middle Ages, the political and cultural centre of Laconia shifted to the nearby settlement of Mystras, and Sparta fell further in even local importance.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Modern Sparta was re-founded in 1834, by a decree of King Otto of Greece.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Today it is a provincial town and the capital of the Laconia administrative region.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The state was ruled by two hereditary kings of the Agiad and Eurypontid families, both supposedly descendants of Heracles and equal in authority, so that one could not act against the power and political enactments of his colleague.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The duties of the kings were primarily religious, judicial, and military.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As chief priests of the state, they maintained communication with the Delphian sanctuary, whose pronouncements exercised great authority in Spartan politics.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] 450 BC, their judicial functions had been restricted to cases dealing with heiresses (epikleroi), adoptions and the public roads (the meaning of the last term is unclear in Herodotus's text and has been interpreted in a number of ways).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Aristotle describes the kingship at Sparta as "a kind of unlimited and perpetual generalship" (Pol. iii.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] 1285a), while Isocrates refers to the Spartans as "subject to an oligarchy at home, to a kingship on campaign" (iii.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Civil and criminal cases were decided by a group of officials known as the ephors, as well as a council of elders known as the Gerousia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Gerousia consisted of 28 elders over the age of 60, elected for life and usually part of the royal households, and the two kings.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] High state decisions were discussed by this council, who could then propose policies to the *damos*, the collective body of Spartan citizenry, who would select one of the alternatives by vote.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Royal prerogatives were curtailed over time.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] From the period of the Persian wars, the king lost the right to declare war and was accompanied in the field by two ephors.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] He was supplanted by the ephors also in the control of foreign policy.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Over time, the kings became mere figureheads except in their capacity as generals.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Political power was transferred to the ephors and Gerousia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] An assembly of citizens called the Ekklesia was responsible for electing men to the Gerousia for life.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartan education process known as the *agoge* was essential for full citizenship.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, usually the only boys eligible for the *agoge* were Spartiates, those who could trace their ancestry to the original inhabitants of the city.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] *Trophimoi* or "foster sons" were foreign students invited to study.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Athenian general Xenophon, for example, sent his two sons to Sparta as trophimoi.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Also, the son of a helot could be enrolled as a *syntrophos* if a Spartiate formally adopted him and paid his way; if he did exceptionally well in training, he might be sponsored to become a Spartiate.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartans who could not afford to pay the expenses of the *agoge* could lose their citizenship.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These laws meant that Sparta could not readily replace citizens lost in battle or otherwise, which eventually proved near fatal as citizens became greatly outnumbered by non-citizens, and even more dangerously by helots.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The other classes were the perioikoi, free inhabitants who were non-citizens, and the helots, state-owned serfs.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Descendants of non-Spartan citizens were forbidden the *agoge*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartans were a minority of the Lakonian population.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The largest class of inhabitants were the helots (in Classical Greek Εἵλωτες / *Heílôtes*).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The helots were originally free Greeks from the areas of Messenia and Lakonia whom the Spartans had defeated in battle and subsequently enslaved.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The helots' position has been described as "serf-like" and they were treated harshly by their masters.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartan helots were not only agricultural workers, but were also household servants, both male and female would be assigned domestic duties, such as wool-working.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, the helots were not the private property of individual Spartan citizens, regardless of their household duties, and were instead owned by the state through the *kleros* system.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Helots did not have voting or political rights.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartan poet Tyrtaios refers to Helots being allowed to marry and retaining 50% of the fruits of their labour.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] They also seem to have been allowed to practice religious rites and, according to Thucydides, own a limited amount of personal property.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Initially, helots couldn't be freed but during the middle Hellenistic period, some 6,000 helots accumulated enough wealth to buy their freedom, for example, in 227 BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In other Greek city-states, free citizens were part-time soldiers who, when not at war, carried on other trades.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Since Spartan men were full-time soldiers, they were not available to carry out manual labour.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The helots were used as unskilled serfs, tilling Spartan land.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Helot women were often used as wet nurses.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Helots also travelled with the Spartan army as non-combatant serfs.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] At the last stand of the Battle of Thermopylae, the Greek dead included not just the legendary three hundred Spartan soldiers but also several hundred Thespian and Theban troops and a number of helots.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] 465–460 BC) that led to prolonged conflict.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] By the tenth year of this war the Spartans and Messenians had reached an agreement in which Messenian rebels were allowed to leave the Peloponnese.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] They were given safe passage under the terms that they would be re-enslaved if they tried to return.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This agreement ended the most serious incursion into Spartan territory since their expansion in the seventh and eighth centuries BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Slave revolts occurred elsewhere in the Greek world, and in 413 BC 20,000 Athenian slaves ran away to join the Spartan forces occupying Attica.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The homogeneous population of Messenian helots who could form families, kept kinship ties and owned some personal items posed a constant threat of rebellion.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] As the Spartiate population declined and the helot population continued to grow, the imbalance of power caused increasing tension.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Each year when the Ephors took office, they ritually declared war on the helots, allowing Spartans to kill them without risk of ritual pollution.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This fight seems to have been carried out by *kryptai* (sing. κρύπτης *kryptēs*), graduates of the *agoge* who took part in the mysterious institution known as the *Krypteia*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Perioikoi came from similar origins as the helots but occupied a significantly different position in Spartan society.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Although they did not enjoy full citizen-rights, they were free and not subjected to the same restrictions as the helots.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The exact nature of their subjection to the Spartans is not clear, but they seem to have served partly as a kind of military reserve, partly as skilled craftsmen and partly as agents of foreign trade.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Full citizen Spartiates were barred by law from trade or manufacture, which consequently rested in the hands of the Perioikoi.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This lucrative monopoly, in a fertile territory with a good harbours, ensured the loyalty of the perioikoi.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Despite the prohibition on menial labour or trade, there is evidence of Spartan sculptors, and Spartans were certainly poets, magistrates, ambassadors, and governors as well as soldiers.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Allegedly, Spartans were prohibited from possessing gold and silver coins, and according to legend Spartan currency consisted of iron bars to discourage hoarding.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Though the conspicuous display of wealth appears to have been discouraged, this did not preclude the production of very fine decorated bronze, ivory and wooden works of art as well as exquisite jewellery, attested in archaeology.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Allegedly as part of the Lycurgan Reforms in the mid-8th century BC, a massive land reform had divided property into 9,000 equal portions.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Each citizen received one estate, a *kleros*, which was expected to provide his living.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The land was worked by helots who retained half the yield.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] From the other half, the Spartiate was expected to pay his mess (*syssitia*) fees, and the *agoge* fees for his children.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, nothing is known of matters of wealth such as how land was bought, sold, and inherited, or whether daughters received dowries.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, from early on there were marked differences of wealth within the state, and these became more serious after the law of Epitadeus some time after the Peloponnesian War, which removed the legal prohibition on the gift or bequest of land.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] By the mid-5th century, land had become concentrated in the hands of a tiny elite, and the notion that all Spartan citizens were equals had become an empty pretence.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] By Aristotle's day (384–322 BC) citizenship had been reduced from 9,000 to less than 1,000, then further decreased to 700 at the accession of Agis IV in 244 BC.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Attempts were made to remedy this by imposing legal penalties upon bachelors, but this could not reverse the trend.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta was above all a militarist state, and emphasis on military fitness began virtually at birth.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] According to Plutarch, after birth, a mother would bathe her child in wine to see whether the child was strong.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] If the child survived, it was brought before the Gerousia by the child's father.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Gerousia then decided whether it was to be reared or not.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] It is commonly stated that if they considered it "puny and deformed", the baby was thrown into a chasm on Mount Taygetos known euphemistically as the *Apothetae* (Gr., *ἀποθέται*, "Deposits").
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This would, in effect, be a primitive form of eugenics.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Plutarch is the sole historical source for the Spartan practice of systemic infanticide motivated by eugenics.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta is often viewed as being unique in this regard, however, anthropologist Laila Williamson notes: "Infanticide has been practiced on every continent and by people on every level of cultural complexity, from hunter gatherers to high civilisations.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan burial customs changed over time.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] When Spartans died, marked headstones would only be granted to soldiers who died in combat during a victorious campaign or women who died either in service of a divine office or in childbirth.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These headstones likely acted as memorials, rather than as grave markers.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Evidence of Spartan burials is provided by the Tomb of the Lacedaimonians in Athens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Excavations at the cemetery of classical Sparta, uncovered ritually pierced kantharoid-like ceramic vessels, the ritual slaughter of horses, and specific burial enclosures alongside individual 'plots'.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Some of the graves were reused over time.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In the Hellenistic Period, grander, two-storey monumental tombs are found at Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Ten of these have been found for this period.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] When male Spartans began military training at age seven, they would enter the *agoge* system.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The *agoge* was designed to encourage discipline and physical toughness and to emphasise the importance of the Spartan state.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Besides physical and weapons training, boys studied reading, writing, music and dancing.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Special punishments were imposed if boys failed to answer questions sufficiently "laconically" (i.e. briefly and wittily).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan boys were expected to take an older male mentor, usually an unmarried young man.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] According to some sources, the older man was expected to function as a kind of substitute father and role model to his junior partner; however, others believe it was reasonably certain that they had sexual relations (the exact nature of Spartan pederasty is not entirely clear).
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Xenophon, an admirer of the Spartan educational system whose sons attended the *agoge*, explicitly denies the sexual nature of the relationship.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Some Spartan youth apparently became members of an irregular unit known as the *Krypteia*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The immediate objective of this unit was to seek out and kill vulnerable helot Laconians as part of the larger program of terrorising and intimidating the helot population.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Less information is available about the education of Spartan girls, but they seem to have gone through a fairly extensive formal educational cycle, broadly similar to that of the boys but with less emphasis on military training.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan girls received an education known as *mousikē*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] This included music, dancing, singing and poetry.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Choral dancing was taught so Spartan girls could participate in ritual activities, including the cults of Helen and Artemis.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In this respect, classical Sparta was unique in ancient Greece.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In no other city-state did women receive any kind of formal education.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] At age 20, the Spartan citizen began his membership in one of the *syssitia* (dining messes or clubs), composed of about fifteen members each, of which every citizen was required to be a member.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Here each group learned how to bond and rely on one another.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The Spartans were not eligible for election for public office until the age of 30.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Only native Spartans were considered full citizens and were obliged to undergo the training as prescribed by law, as well as participate in and contribute financially to one of the *syssitia*.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta is thought to be the first city to practice athletic nudity, and some scholars claim that it was also the first to formalize pederasty.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] According to these sources, the Spartans believed that the love of an older, accomplished aristocrat for an adolescent was essential to his formation as a free citizen.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The *agoge*, the education of the ruling class, was, they claim, founded on pederastic relationships required of each citizen, with the lover responsible for the boy's training.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] However, other scholars question this interpretation.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Xenophon explicitly denies it, but not Plutarch.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan men remained in the active reserve until age 60.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Men were encouraged to marry at age 20 but could not live with their families until they left their active military service at age 30.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] They called themselves "*homoioi*" (equals), pointing to their common lifestyle and the discipline of the phalanx, which demanded that no soldier be superior to his comrades.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Insofar as hoplite warfare could be perfected, the Spartans did so.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartans buried their battle dead on or near the battle field; corpses were not brought back on their shield.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Nevertheless, it is fair to say that it was less of a disgrace for a soldier to lose his helmet, breastplate or greaves than his shield, since the former were designed to protect one man, whereas the shield also protected the man on his left.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Thus, the shield was symbolic of the individual soldier's subordination to his unit, his integral part in its success, and his solemn responsibility to his comrades in arms – messmates and friends, often close blood relations.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] One of the most persistent myths about Sparta is the notion that Spartan mothers were without feelings toward their off-spring and helped enforce a militaristic lifestyle on their sons and husbands.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The myth can be traced back to Plutarch, who includes no less than 17 "sayings" of "Spartan women", all of which paraphrase or elaborate on the theme that Spartan mothers rejected their own offspring if they showed any kind of cowardice.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] In some of these sayings, mothers revile their sons in insulting language merely for surviving a battle.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These sayings purporting to be from Spartan women were far more likely to be of Athenian origin and designed to portray Spartan women as unnatural and so undeserving of pity.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Sparta's agriculture consisted mainly of barley, wine, cheese, grain, and figs.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These items were grown locally on each Spartan citizen's kleros and were tended to by helots.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] Spartan citizens were required to donate a certain amount of what they yielded from their kleros to their syssitia, or mess.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These donations to the syssitia were a requirement for every Spartan citizen.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] All the donated food was then redistributed to feed the Spartan population of that syssitia.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The helots who tended to the lands were fed using a portion of what they harvested.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The husband continued to visit his wife in secret for some time after the marriage.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] These customs, unique to the Spartans, have been interpreted in various ways.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] One of them decidedly supports the need to disguise the bride as a man in order to help the bridegroom consummate the marriage, so unaccustomed were men to women's looks at the time of their first intercourse.
[src:sparta/sparta-p01] The "abduction" may have served to ward off the evil eye, and the cutting of the wife's hair was perhaps part of a rite of passage that signalled her entrance into a new life.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Spartan women, of the citizenry class, enjoyed a status, power, and respect that was unknown in the rest of the classical world.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The higher status of females in Spartan society started at birth; unlike Athens, Spartan girls were fed the same food as their brothers.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Nor were they confined to their father's house and prevented from exercising or getting fresh air as in Athens, but exercised and even competed in sports.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Most important, rather than being married off at the age of 12 or 13, Spartan law forbade the marriage of a girl until she was in her late teens or early 20s.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The reasons for delaying marriage were to ensure the birth of healthy children, but the effect was to spare Spartan women the hazards and lasting health damage associated with pregnancy among adolescents.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Spartan women, better fed from childhood and fit from exercise, stood a far better chance of reaching old age than their sisters in other Greek cities, where the median age for death was 34.6 years or roughly 10 years below that of men.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Unlike Athenian women who wore heavy, concealing clothes and were rarely seen outside the house, Spartan women wore dresses (peplos) slit up the side to allow freer movement and moved freely about the city, either walking or driving chariots.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Girls as well as boys exercised, possibly in the nude, and young women as well as young men may have participated in the Gymnopaedia ("Festival of Nude Youths").
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Another practice that was mentioned by many visitors to Sparta was the practice of "wife-sharing".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] In accordance with the Spartan belief that breeding should be between the most physically fit parents, many older men allowed younger, more fit men, to impregnate their wives.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Other unmarried or childless men might even request another man's wife to bear his children if she had previously been a strong child bearer.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] For this reason many considered Spartan women polygamous or polyandrous.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] This practice was encouraged in order that women bear as many strong-bodied children as they could.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The Spartan population was hard to maintain due to the constant absence and loss of the men in battle and the intense physical inspection of newborns.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Spartan women were also literate and numerate, a rarity in the ancient world.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Furthermore, as a result of their education and the fact that they moved freely in society engaging with their fellow (male) citizens, they were notorious for speaking their minds even in public.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Plato, in the middle of the fourth century, described women's curriculum in Sparta as consisting of gymnastics and mousike (music and arts).
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Plato praised Spartan women's ability when it came to philosophical discussion.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Most importantly, Spartan women had economic power because they controlled their own properties, and those of their husbands.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] It is estimated that in later Classical Sparta, when the male population was in serious decline, women were the sole owners of at least 35% of all land and property in Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The laws regarding a divorce were the same for both men and women.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Unlike women in Athens, if a Spartan woman became the heiress of her father because she had no living brothers to inherit (an *epikleros*), the woman was not required to divorce her current spouse in order to marry her nearest paternal relative.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Many women played a significant role in the history of Sparta.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Queen Gorgo, heiress to the throne and the wife of Leonidas I, was an influential and well-documented figure.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Herodotus records that as a small girl she advised her father Cleomenes to resist a bribe.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] She was later said to be responsible for decoding a warning that the Persian forces were about to invade Greece; after Spartan generals could not decode a wooden tablet covered in wax, she ordered them to clear the wax, revealing the warning.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Plutarch's *Moralia* contains a collection of "Sayings of Spartan Women", including a laconic quip attributed to Gorgo: when asked by a woman from Attica why Spartan women were the only women in the world who could rule men, she replied "Because we are the only women who are mothers of men".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] In 396, Cynisca, sister of the Eurypontid king Agesilaus II, became the first woman in Greece to win an Olympic chariot race.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] She won again in 392, and dedicated two monuments to commemorate her victory, these being an inscription in Sparta and a set of bronze equestrian statues at the Olympic temple of Zeus.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Laconophilia is love or admiration of Sparta and its culture or constitution.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Sparta was subject of considerable admiration in its day, even in rival Athens.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The French classicist François Ollier in his 1933 book *Le mirage spartiate* (The Spartan Mirage) warned that a major scholarly problem is that all surviving accounts of Sparta were by non-Spartans who often excessively idealised their subject.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The term "Spartan Mirage" has come to refer to "idealized distortions and inventions regarding the character of Spartan society in the works of non-Spartan writers," beginning in Greek and Roman antiquity and continuing through the medieval and modern eras.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] These accounts of Sparta are typically associated with the social or political concerns of the writer.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] No accounts survive by the Spartans themselves, if such were ever written.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] With the revival of classical learning in Renaissance Europe, Laconophilia re-appeared, for example in the writings of Machiavelli.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The Elizabethan English constitutionalist John Aylmer compared the mixed government of Tudor England to the Spartan republic, stating that "Lacedemonia [was] the noblest and best city governed that ever was".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The philosopher Jean-Jacques Rousseau contrasted Sparta favourably with Athens in his *Discourse on the Arts and Sciences*, arguing that its austere constitution was preferable to the more sophisticated Athenian life.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Sparta was also used as a model of austere purity by Revolutionary and Napoleonic France.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] A German strain of Laconophilia was initiated by Karl Otfried Müller, who linked Spartan ideals to the supposed racial superiority of the Dorians, the ethnic sub-group of the Greeks to which the Spartans belonged.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] In the 20th century, this developed into admiration of Spartan ideals by the National Socialists.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Adolf Hitler praised the Spartans, recommending in 1928 that Germany should imitate them by limiting "the number allowed to live".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] He added that "The Spartans were once capable of such a wise measure...
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The subjugation of 350,000 Helots by 6,000 Spartans was only possible because of the racial superiority of the Spartans." The Spartans had created "the first racialist state".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Following the invasion of the USSR, Hitler viewed citizens of the USSR as like the helots under the Spartans: "They [the Spartans] came as conquerors, and they took everything", and so should the Germans.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Certain early Zionists, and particularly the founders of Kibbutz movement in Israel, were influenced by Spartan ideals, particularly in education.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Tabenkin, a founding father of the Kibbutz movement and the Palmach strikeforce, prescribed that education for warfare "should begin from the nursery", that children should from kindergarten be taken to "spend nights in the mountains and valleys".
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] In modern times, the adjective "Spartan" means simple, frugal, avoiding luxury and comfort.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] The term "laconic phrase" describes the very terse and direct speech characteristic of the Spartans.
[src:sparta/sparta-p02] Sparta also features prominently in modern popular culture, most famously the Battle of Thermopylae (see Battle of Thermopylae in popular culture).
